{"title_page": "Carlos Villar\u00edas", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Carlos Villar\u00edas\n| caption       = Carlos Villarias, was best known for his role of \"Dracula\" in the Spanish language version of the same title\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1892|7|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1976|4|27|1892|7|7|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Los Angeles]], California, [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active   = 1917\u20131953\n}}\n\n'''Carlos Villar\u00edas''' (7 July 1892 \u2013 27 April 1976) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] actor who was born in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]] and died in [[California, USA]]. His most famous role is in the title role of the [[Spanish language]] version of ''[[Dracula (1931 Spanish-language film)|Dr\u00e1cula]]'' (1931), with [[Barry Norton]] and [[Lupita Tovar]] filmed at night on the same sets as the English language [[Dracula (1931 English-language film)|version]] starring [[Bela Lugosi]].\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n* ''[[Dracula (1931 Spanish-language film)|Dracula]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Road of Hell (1931 film)|Road of Hell]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[The California Trail]]'' (1933)\n* ''The Mystery of the Ghastly Face'' (1935)\n* ''[[Mis dos amores]]''  (1938)\n* ''[[La Inmaculada]]''  (1939)\n* ''[[Summer Hotel]]'' (1944)\n* ''[[Gran Hotel (film)|Gran Hotel]]'' (1944)\n* ''[[The Museum of Crime]]'' (1945)\n* ''[[The Private Life of Mark Antony and Cleopatra]]'' (1947)\n* ''[[Adventure in the Night]]'' (1948)\n* ''[[Zorina (film)|Zorina]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Lola Casanova]]'' (1949)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|0898107}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Villarias, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish male film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish male actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish emigrants to the United States]]\n\n\n{{film-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Carlos Villar\u00edas\n| caption       = Carlos Villarias, was best known for his role of \"Dracula\" in the Spanish language version of the same title\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1892|7|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1976|4|27|1892|7|7|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Los Angeles]], California, [[United States|U.S.]]\n| occupation    = Actor\n| years_active   = 1917\u20131953\n}}\n\n'''Carlos Villar\u00edas''' (7 July 1892 \u2013 27 April 1976) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] actor who was born in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]] and died in [[California, USA]]. His most famous role is in the title role of the [[Spanish language]] version of ''[[Dracula (1931 Spanish-language film)|Dr\u00e1cula]]'' (1931), with [[Barry Norton]] and [[Lupita Tovar]] filmed at night on the same sets as the English language [[Dracula (1931 English-language film)|version]] starring [[Bela Lugosi]].\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n* ''[[Dracula (1931 Spanish-language film)|Dracula]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Road of Hell (1931 film)|Road of Hell]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[The California Trail]]'' (1933)\n*  ''The Mystery of the Ghastly Face'' (1935)\n* ''[[Mis dos amores]]''  (1938)\n* ''[[La Inmaculada]]''  (1939)\n* ''[[Summer Hotel]]'' (1944)\n* ''[[Gran Hotel (film)|Gran Hotel]]'' (1944)\n* ''[[The Museum of Crime]]'' (1945)\n* ''[[The Private Life of Mark Antony and Cleopatra]]'' (1947)\n* ''[[Adventure in the Night]]'' (1948)\n* ''[[Zorina (film)|Zorina]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Lola Casanova]]'' (1949)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|0898107}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Villarias, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:People 