{"title_page": "David Dalrymple (Australian politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = '''[[The Honourable]]'''\n|name               = David Dalrymple\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              = StateLibQld 1 143235 David H. Dalrymple, MLA.jpg\n| caption \t\t  = \n\n| constituency_AM1  = [[Electoral district of Mackay|Mackay]]\n| assembly1         = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start1       = 5 May 1888\n| term_end1         = 27 August 1904\n| predecessor1      = New seat\n| successor1        = [[Albert Fudge]]\n| alongside1        = [[Maurice Hume Black|Maurice Black]], [[James Chataway]], [[Walter Paget]]\n\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1840|12|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[Berkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date \t  = {{death date and age|1912|9|1|1840|12|14|df=y}}\n| death_place \t  = [[Hamilton, Queensland|Queensland]], [[Australia]]\n|restingplace       = [[Toowong Cemetery]]\n|birthname          = David Hay Dalrymple\n|nationality        = [[English Australian]]\n|party              = Ministerial\n|otherparty         = \n|spouse             = Euphemia Margaret McLean (m.1880)\n | known_for                    = \n| occupation        = [[Chemist]]\n| relations         = \n| alma_mater        =\n| religion          = [[Church of England]]\n}}\n\n'''David Hay Dalrymple'''  was a  pastoralist, chemist/druggist, and politician in [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=1933380671|title=Former Members Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=Queensland Parliament|publisher=|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref> He was a [[Mayor of Mackay]] and a Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland|Queensland Legislative Assembly]]. \n\n== Early life ==\nDalrymple was born on 14 December 1840 in [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[Berkshire]], England, the son of James Dalrymple and his wife Georgina (n\u00e9e Hay). He was educated at the [[Independent College, Taunton|Independent College]] in [[Taunton]] and attended lectures at the [[Bristol Medical School]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDalrymple arrived in [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]] in 1863.  He was married to Euphemia Margaret McLean in Mackay on 23 Dec 1880 and had two sons and two daughters.  He was a pastoralist, chemist and druggist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/dalrymple-david-hay-5871|title=Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref> \n\n== Politics ==\nDalrymple served on community boards and served as the [[Mayor of Mackay]] from 1869\u20131871 and again in 1873\u20131874.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/36393773|title=Mackay City Council representatives : '1869-2008'|author1=Wright, Berenice D|author2=Mackay. Libraries. Local History Section|publisher=Mackay City Council|publication-date=2009|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was a Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland|Queensland Legislative Assembly]] for [[Electoral district of Mackay|Mackay]] from 5 May 1888 to 27 August 1904.<ref name=\"qpm\">{{Cite QldMLA|accessdate=13 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\nDalrymple died from heart failure in his sleep at his residence ''Dalry'' at Crescent Road, [[Hamilton, Queensland|Hamilton]], [[Brisbane]], Queensland on 1 September 1912.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article19851385 |title=HON. D. H. DALRYMPLE. |newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]  |issue=17,048  |location=Queensland, Australia |date=2 September 1912 |accessdate=17 March 2016 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He was buried in [[Toowong Cemetery]] on 2 September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article19851405|title=Family Notices|date=2 September 1912|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=13 November 2017|issue=17,048|location=Queensland, Australia|page=6|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Flags were flown at half-mast in Mackay as a mark of respect.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article168631222|title=The Late Hon. D. H. Dalrymple.|date=3 September 1912|newspaper=[[Daily Mercury]]|accessdate=13 November 2017|location=Queensland, Australia|page=4|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-qld }}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl |title= Member for [[Electoral district of Mackay|Mackay]]|years=1888&ndash;1904|alongside=[[Maurice Hume Black|Maurice Black]], [[James Chataway]], [[Walter Paget]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fudge]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dalrymple, David}}\n[[Category:Members of the Queensland Legislative Assembly]]\n\n{{Australia-politician-stub}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Toowong Cemetery]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = '''[[The Honourable]]'''\n|name               = David Dalrymple\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              = StateLibQld 1 143235 David H. Dalrymple, MLA.jpg\n| caption \t\t  = \n\n| constituency_AM1  = [[Electoral district of Mackay|Mackay]]\n| assembly1         = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start1       = 5 May 1888\n| term_end1         = 27 August 1904\n| predecessor1      = New seat\n| successor1        = [[Albert Fudge]]\n| alongside1        = [[Maurice Hume Black|Maurice Black]], [[James Chataway]], [[Walter Paget]]\n\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1840|12|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[Berkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date \t  = {{death date and age|1912|9|1|1840|12|14|df=y}}\n| death_place \t  = [[Hamilton, Queensland|Queensland]], [[Australia]]\n|restingplace       = [[Toowong Cemetery]]\n|birthname          = David Hay Dalrymple\n|nationality        = [[English Australian]]\n|party              = Ministerial\n|otherparty         = \n|spouse             = Euphemia Margaret McLean (m.1880)\n | known_for                    = \n| occupation        = [[Chemist]]\n| relations         = \n| alma_mater        =\n| religion          = [[Church of England]]\n}}\n\n'''David Hay Dalrymple'''  was a  pastoralist, chemist/druggist, and politician in [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=1933380671|title=Former Members Bio|last=|first=|date=|website=Queensland Parliament|publisher=|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref> He was a [[Mayor of Mackay]] and a Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland|Queensland Legislative Assembly]]. \n\n== Early life ==\nDalrymple was born on 14 December 1840 in [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[Berkshire]], England, the son of James Dalrymple and his wife Georgina (n\u00e9e Hay). He was educated at the [[Independent College, Taunton|Independent College]] in [[Taunton]] and attended lectures at the [[Bristol Medical School]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDalrymple arrived in [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]] in 1863.  He was married to Euphemia Margaret McLean in Mackay on 23 Dec 1880 and had two sons and two daughters.  He was a pastoralist, chemist and druggist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/dalrymple-david-hay-5871|title=Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref> \n\n== Politics ==\nDalrymple served on community boards and served as the [[Mayor of Mackay]] from 1869 - 1871 and again in 1873\u20131874.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/36393773|title=Mackay City Council representatives : '1869-2008'|author1=Wright, Berenice D|author2=Mackay. Libraries. Local History Section|publisher=Mackay City Council|publication-date=2009|accessdate=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was a Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland|Queensland Legislative Assembly]] for [[Electoral district of Mackay|Mackay]] from 5 May 1888 to 27 August 1904.<ref name=\"qpm\">{{Cite QldMLA|accessdate=13 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\nDalrymple died from heart failure in his sleep at his residence ''Dalry'' at Crescent Road, [[Hamilton, Queensland|Hamilton]], [[Brisbane]], Queensland on 1 September 1912.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article19851385 |title=HON. D. H. DALRYMPLE. |newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]  |issue=17,048  |location=Queensland, Australia |date=2 September 1912 |accessdate=17 March 2016 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> He was buried in [[Toowong Cemetery]] on 2 September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article19851405|title=Family Notices|date=2 September 1912|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=13 November 2017|issue=17,048|location=Queensland, Australia|page=6|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Flags were flown at half-mast in Mackay as a mark of respect.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article168631222|title=The Late Hon. D. H. Dalrymple.|date=3 September 1912|newspaper=[[Daily Mercury]]|accessdate=13 November 2017|location=Queensland, Australia|page=4|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-qld }}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl |title= Member for [[Electoral district of Mackay|Mackay]]|years=1888&ndash;1904|alongside=[[Maurice Hume Black|Maurice Black]], [[James Chataway]], [[Walter Paget]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fudge]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dalrymple, David}}\n[[Category:Members of the Queensland Legislative Assembly]]\n\n{{Australia-politician-stub}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Toowong Cemetery]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Australia]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitics:dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Dalrymple_(Australian_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Future", "text_new": "{{redirect|Near future|near future events|Timeline of the near future}}\n{{Other uses|Future (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Time which has yet to occur}}\n[[File:The Last of the Spirits-John Leech, 1843.jpg|right|175px|thumb|The [[Ghost of Christmas Yet to Come]] shows [[Ebenezer Scrooge|Scrooge]] his future in [[Charles Dickens|Dickens']] ''[[A Christmas Carol]]''.]]\n{{Human history}}\n\nThe '''future''' is the [[time]] after the [[present]]. Its arrival is considered inevitable due to the existence of [[time]] and the [[laws of physics]].  Due to the apparent nature of [[reality]] and the unavoidability of the future, everything that currently [[wikt: exist|exists]] and will exist can be categorized as either permanent, meaning that it will exist forever, or temporary, meaning that it will end.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UD8TAAAAYAAJ ''Encyclop\u00e6dia of religion and ethics'']. Edinburgh: T. & T. Clark. pp. 335\u2013337.</ref> In the [[Western culture|Occidental]] view, which uses a linear conception of time, the future is the portion of the projected timeline that is anticipated to occur.<ref>Moore, C.-L. & Yamamoto, K. (1988). ''Beyond words: movement observation and analysis''. New York: Gordon and Breach. p. 57. (cf., The representation of time as a linear, unidirectional progression is a distinctly Occidental point of view.)</ref> In [[special relativity]], the future is considered [[absolute future]], or the future [[light cone]].<ref>Eddington, A. S. (1921). [https://archive.org/details/spacetimeandgra00eddigoog ''Space, time and gravitation; an outline of the general relativity theory'']. Cambridge: University Press. p. 107.</ref>\n\nIn the [[philosophy of time]], [[Philosophical presentism|presentism]] is the [[belief]] that only the present [[existence|exists]] and the future and the past are [[reality|unreal]]. Religions consider the future when they address issues such as [[karma]], [[afterlife|life after death]], and [[eschatology|eschatologies]] that study what the end of time and the end of the world will be. Religious figures such as [[prophet]]s and [[divination|diviners]] have claimed to see into the future. \nFuture studies, or [[futurology]], is the science, art, and practice of postulating possible futures. Modern practitioners stress the importance of alternative and plural futures, rather than one monolithic future, and the limitations of prediction and [[probability]], versus the creation of possible and preferable futures.\n\nThe concept of the future has been explored extensively in cultural production, including [[art]] movements and genres devoted entirely to its elucidation, such as the 20th-century movement [[futurism]].\n\n==Physics==\n[[File:World line.svg|250px|right|thumb|A visualization of the future [[light cone]] (at the top), the present, and the past light cone in 2D space.]]\n{{See also|Time in physics}}\nIn physics, time is the fourth dimension. Physicists argue that [[spacetime]] can be understood as a sort of Your hart. Time flies. fabric that bends due to forces such as gravity. In [[classical physics]] the future is just a half of the timeline, which is the same for all observers. In [[special relativity]] the flow of time is relative to the observer's [[frame of reference]]. The faster an observer is traveling away from a reference object, the slower that object seems to move through time. Hence, the future is not an objective notion anymore. A more modern notion is [[absolute future]], or the future [[light cone]]. While a person can move backward or forwards in the three spatial dimensions, many physicists argue you are only able to move forward in time.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.livescience.com/technology/070307_time_travel.html|title=You Can't Travel Back in Time, Scientists Say|publisher=|accessdate=31 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOne of the outcomes of Special Relativity Theory is that a person can travel into the future (but never come back) by traveling at very high speeds. While this effect is negligible under ordinary conditions, space travel at very high speeds can change the flow of time considerably. As depicted in many [[science fiction]] stories and movies (e.g. ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]''), a person traveling for even a short time at near [[light speed]] will return to an Earth that is many years in the future.\n\nSome physicists claim that by using a [[wormhole]] to connect two regions of spacetime a person could theoretically travel in time. Physicist [[Michio Kaku]] points out that to power this hypothetical time machine and \"punch a hole into the fabric of space-time\", it would require the energy of a star. Another theory is that a person could travel in time with [[cosmic string]]s.\n\n==Philosophy==\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = \"The trouble with the future is that it's so much less knowable than the past.\" \n| source =&nbsp;[[John Lewis Gaddis]], ''The Landscape of History''.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Landscape of History: How Historians Map the Past |last= Gaddis|first= John Lewis|year= 2002|publisher= Oxford University Press|location= New York|isbn= 978-0-19-517157-0|pages= 56}}\n&nbsp;</ref> \n| width  = 27%\n| align  = right\n| style = padding:8px;\n}}\n\nIn the [[philosophy of time]], presentism is the [[belief]] that only the present [[existence|exists]], and the future and [[past]] are [[reality|unreal]]. Past and future \"entities\" are construed as [[logic]]al constructions or [[fictionalism|fictions]]. The opposite of presentism is '[[Eternalism (philosophy of time)|eternalism]]', which is the belief that things in the past and things yet to come exist [[eternity|eternally]]. Another view (not held by many philosophers) is sometimes called the '[[Growing block universe|growing block]]' [[theory]] of time\u2014which postulates that the past and present exist, but the future does not.<ref>{{cite book| last=Broad| first= C.D.| title= Scientific Thought| location=New York| publisher=Harcourt, Brace and Co.| year=1923| url=http://www.ditext.com/broad/st/st-con.html}}</ref>\n\nPresentism is [[wikt: compatible|compatible]] with [[Galilean relativity]], in which time is independent of space, but is probably incompatible with [[Hendrik Lorentz|Lorentz]]ian/[[Einstein]]ian relativity in conjunction with certain other philosophical [[thesis|theses]] that many find uncontroversial. [[Augustine of Hippo|Saint Augustine]] [[Research proposal|proposed]] that the present is a knife edge between the past and the future and could not contain any extended period of time.\n\nContrary to Saint Augustine, some philosophers propose that conscious experience is extended in time.  For instance, [[William James]] said that time is \"...the short duration of which we are immediately and incessantly sensible.\"{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}  Augustine proposed that God is outside of time and present for all times, in [[eternity]]. Other early philosophers who were presentists include the [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (in the tradition of [[Indian Buddhism]]). A leading scholar from the modern era on [[Buddhist philosophy]] is [[Theodor Ippolitovich Stcherbatsky|Stcherbatsky]], who has written extensively on Buddhist presentism: {{cquote|Everything past is unreal, everything future is unreal, everything imagined, absent, mental... is unreal... Ultimately real is only the present moment of physical [[wikt:efficiency|efficiency]] [i.e., [[Causality|causation]]].<ref>Vol.1 of ''Buddhist Logic'', 1962, Dover: New York. 70\u201371.</ref>}}\n\n==Psychology==\n{{unreferenced section|date=October 2018}}\n[[Human behavior]] is known to encompass anticipation of the future. Anticipatory behavior can be the result of a psychological outlook toward the future, for examples [[optimism]], [[pessimism]], and [[hope]].\n\nOptimism is an outlook on life such that one maintains a view of the world as a positive place. People would say that optimism is seeing the glass \"half full\" of water as opposed to half empty. It is the philosophical opposite of pessimism. Optimists generally believe that people and events are inherently good, so that most situations work out in the end for the best. Hope is a belief in a positive outcome related to events and circumstances in one's life. Hope implies a certain amount of despair, wanting, wishing, suffering or perseverance\u2014i.e., believing that a better or positive outcome is possible even when there is some evidence to the contrary. \"Hopefulness\" is somewhat different from optimism in that hope is an emotional state, whereas optimism is a conclusion reached through a deliberate thought pattern that leads to a positive attitude.\n\n[[Pessimism]] as stated before is the opposite of optimism. It is the tendency to see, anticipate, or emphasize only bad or undesirable outcomes, results, or problems. The word originates in Latin from Pessimus meaning worst and Malus meaning bad.\n\n==Religion==\nReligions consider the future when they address issues such as [[karma]], [[afterlife|life after death]], and [[eschatology|eschatologies]] that study what the end of time and the end of the world will be. In religion, major prophets are said to have the power to change the future.  Common religious figures have claimed to see into the future, such as minor [[prophet]]s and [[divination|diviners]].\nThe term \"afterlife\" refers to the continuation of [[existence]] of the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]], [[spirit]] or [[mind]] of a human (or animal) after physical [[death]], typically in a [[Spirituality|spiritual]] or [[ghost]]like afterworld. Deceased persons are usually believed to go to a specific region or [[planes of existence|plane of existence]] in this afterworld, often depending on the rightness of their actions during life.\n\nSome believe the afterlife includes some form of preparation for the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]] to transfer to another body ([[reincarnation]]).\nThe major views on the afterlife derive from [[religion]], [[esotericism]] and [[metaphysics]]. There are those who are skeptical of the existence of the afterlife, or believe that it is absolutely impossible, such as the [[materialism|materialist]]-reductionists, who believe that the topic is [[supernatural]], therefore does not really exist or is unknowable. In metaphysical models, [[theists]] generally, believe some sort of afterlife awaits people when they die. [[Atheism|Atheists]] generally do not believe in a life after death. Members of some generally non-theistic religions such as [[Buddhism]], tend to believe in an afterlife like [[reincarnation]] but without reference to [[God]].\n\n[[Agnosticism|Agnostics]] generally hold the position that like the existence of God, the existence of supernatural phenomena, such as souls or life after death, is unverifiable and therefore unknowable.<ref>{{cite dictionary | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/agnostic | title=agnositic | dictionary=Merriam-Webster | accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> Many religions, whether they believe in the soul's existence in another world like Christianity, Islam and many [[Paganism|pagan]] belief systems, or in reincarnation like many forms of Hinduism and Buddhism, believe that one's status in the afterlife is a reward or punishment for their conduct during life, with the exception of [[Calvinistic]] variants of [[Protestant]] Christianity, which believes one's status in the afterlife is a gift from God and cannot be earned during life.\n\n[[Eschatology]] is a part of [[theology]] and [[philosophy]] concerned with the final events in the [[history of the world]], or the ultimate [[destiny]] of [[All humanity|humanity]], commonly referred to as the end of the world. While in [[mysticism]] the phrase refers metaphorically to the end of ordinary reality and reunion with the Divine, in many traditional [[religion]]s it is taught as an actual future event [[prophecy|prophesied]] in [[sacred text]]s or [[folklore]]. More broadly, eschatology may encompass related concepts such as the [[Messiah]] or [[Messianic Age]], the [[end time]], and the [[End of Days (eschatology)|end of days]].\n\n== Grammar ==\nIn [[grammar]], actions are classified according to one of the following twelve verb tenses: past ([[past]], [[Uses of English verb forms#Past progressive|past continuous]], [[past perfect]], or [[past perfect continuous]]), present ([[present]], [[present continuous]], [[present perfect]], or [[present perfect continuous]]), or future (future, [[future continuous]], [[future perfect]], or [[future perfect continuous]]).<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> The future tense refers to actions that have not yet happened, but which are due, expected, or likely to occur in the future.<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> For example, in the sentence, \"She will walk home,\" the verb \"will walk\" is in the future tense because it refers to an action that is going to, or is likely to, happen at a point in time beyond the present.\n\nVerbs in the future continuous tense indicate actions that will happen beyond the present and will continue for a period of time.<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> In the sentence, \"She will be walking home,\" the [[verb phrase]] \"will be walking\" is in the future continuous tense because the action described is not happening now, but will happen sometime afterwards and is expected to continue happening for some time. Verbs in the future perfect tense indicate actions that will be completed at a particular point in the future.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Merriam-Webster |title=Present Perfect |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/present%20perfect |website=Merriam-Webster.com |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=27 August 2018 |format=Web |date=n.d.}}</ref> For example, the [[verb phrase]], \"will have walked,\" in the sentence, \"She will have walked home,\" is in the future perfect tense because it refers to an action that is completed as of a specific time in the future. Finally, verbs in the future perfect continuous tense combine the features of the perfect and continuous tenses, describing the future status of actions that have been happening continually from now or the past through to a particular time in the future.<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> In the sentence, \"She will have been walking home,\" the verb phrase \"will have been walking\" is in the future perfect continuous tense because it refers to an action that the speaker anticipates will be finished in the future.\n\nAnother way to think of the various future tenses is that actions described by the future tense will be completed at an unspecified time in the future, actions described by the future continuous tense will keep happening in the future, actions described by the future perfect tense will be completed at a specific time in the future, and actions described by the future perfect continuous tense are expected to be continuing as of a specific time in the future.\n\n== Linear and cyclic culture ==\nThe linear view of time (common in [[Western thought]]) draws a stronger distinction between past and future than does the more common [[cyclic time]] of cultures such as India, where past and future can coalesce much more readily.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Ridderbos\n| first1                = Katinka\n| title                 = Time\n| url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=muoM9H8Z8o8C\n| series                = Darwin College Lectures\n| issue                 = 14\n| publisher             = Cambridge University Press\n| publication-date      = 2002\n| page                  = 2\n| isbn                  = 978-0521782937\n| accessdate            = 2015-09-03\n| quote                 = In a cyclic universe, each event that lies in the past of the present moment, also lies in its future. \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Futures studies==\n[[Image: Stanford Torus interior.jpg|thumb|right|Project of an orbital colony [[Stanford torus]], painted by Donald E. Davis]]\n[[Futures studies]] or futurology is the science, art, and practice of postulating possible, probable, and preferable futures and the worldviews and myths that underlie them. Futures studies seek to understand what is likely to continue, what is likely to change, and what is novel. Part of the discipline thus seeks a systematic and pattern-based understanding of past and present, and to determine the likelihood of future events and trends.  A key part of this process is understanding the potential future impact of decisions made by individuals, organizations, and governments.  Leaders use the results of such work to assist in decision-making.\n\n{{cquote|Take hold of the future or the future will take hold of you.<br>{{mdash}}[[Patrick Dixon]], author of ''[[Futurewise (book)|Futurewise]]''}}\nFutures is an interdisciplinary field, studying yesterday's and today's changes, and aggregating and analyzing both lay and professional strategies, and opinions with respect to tomorrow. It includes analyzing the sources, patterns, and causes of change and stability in the attempt to develop foresight and to map possible futures. Modern practitioners stress the importance of alternative and plural futures, rather than one monolithic future, and the limitations of prediction and probability, versus the creation of possible and preferable futures.\n\nThree factors usually distinguish futures studies from the research conducted by other disciplines (although all disciplines overlap, to differing degrees). First, futures studies often examines not only possible but also probable, preferable, and \"wild card\" futures. Second, futures studies typically attempts to gain a holistic or systemic view based on insights from a range of different disciplines. Third, futures studies challenges and unpacks the assumptions behind dominant and contending views of the future. The future thus is not empty but fraught with hidden assumptions.\n\nFutures studies do not generally include the work of economists who forecast movements of interest rates over the next business cycle, or of managers or investors with short-term time horizons. Most strategic planning, which develops operational plans for preferred futures with time horizons of one to three years, is also not considered futures. But plans and strategies with longer time horizons that specifically attempt to anticipate and be robust to possible future events, are part of a major subdiscipline of futures studies called strategic foresight.\n\nThe futures field also excludes those who make future predictions through professed supernatural means. At the same time, it does seek to understand the model's such groups use and the interpretations they give to these models.\n\n===Forecasting===\n{{Main|Forecasting}}\nForecasting is the process of [[Estimation|estimating]] outcomes in uncontrolled situations. Forecasting is applied in many areas, such as [[weather forecasting]], [[earthquake prediction]], [[transport planning]], and [[labour market]] planning. Due to the element of the unknown, [[risk]] and [[uncertainty]] are central to forecasting.\n\nStatistically based forecasting employs [[time series]] with [[cross-sectional data|cross-sectional]] or [[longitudinal study|longitudinal]] data. [[Econometric]] forecasting methods use the assumption that it is possible to identify the underlying factors that might influence the variable that is being forecast. If the causes are understood, projections of the influencing variables can be made and used in the forecast. Judgmental forecasting methods incorporate intuitive judgments, opinions, and probability estimates, as in the case of the [[Delphi method]], [[scenario building]], and [[simulation]]s.\n\nPrediction is similar to forecasting but is used more generally, for instance, to also include baseless claims on the future. Organized efforts to [[prediction|predict]] the future began with practices like [[astrology]], [[haruspicy]], and [[augury]]. These are all considered to be [[pseudoscience]] today, evolving from the human desire to know the future in advance.\n\nModern efforts such as [[futures studies]] attempt to predict technological and societal trends, while more ancient practices, such as weather forecasting, have benefited from [[Scientific modeling|scientific]] and [[causal model]]ling. Despite the development of [[cognition|cognitive]] instruments for the comprehension of future, the [[stochastic process|stochastic]] and [[Chaos theory|chaotic]] nature of many natural and social processes has made precise forecasting of the future elusive.\n\n==In art and culture==\n===Futurism===\n<!--\"Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Layout of building complex\" links here -->\n[[Futurism]] as an [[art movement]] originated in [[Italy]] at the beginning of the 20th century. It developed largely in [[Italy]] and in [[Russia]], although it also had adherents in other countries\u2014in England and Portugal for example. The Futurists explored every medium of art, including [[painting]], [[sculpture]], [[poetry]], [[theatre]], [[music]], [[architecture]], and even [[gastronomy]]. Futurists had passionate loathing of ideas from the past, especially political and artistic traditions. They also espoused a love of [[speed]], [[technology]], and [[violence]]. Futurists dubbed the love of the past ''[[pass\u00e9isme]]''. The car, the plane, and the industrial town were all legendary for the Futurists because they represented the technological triumph of people over [[nature]].  The ''[[Futurist Manifesto]]'' of 1909 declared: \"We will glorify war\u2014the world's only hygiene\u2014militarism, patriotism, the destructive gesture of freedom-bringers, beautiful ideas worth dying for, and scorn for woman.\"<ref name=\"futurmanifest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italianfuturism.org/manifestos/foundingmanifesto/|title=The Founding and Manifesto of Futurism|publisher=italianfuturism.org (Originally published on [[Le Figaro]], [[Paris]], February 20, 1909)}}</ref>  Though it owed much of its character and some of its ideas to [[political radicalism|radical political movements]], it had little involvement in politics until the autumn of 1913.<ref>Martin, Marianne W., p .186</ref>\n\nFuturism in Classical Music arose during this same time period. Closely identified with the central Italian Futurist movement were brother composers [[Luigi Russolo]] (1885\u20131947) and [[Antonio Russolo]] (1877\u20131942), who used instruments known as ''[[intonarumori]]''\u2014essentially [[sound box]]es used to create music out of noise. Luigi Russolo's futurist manifesto, \"[[The Art of Noises]]\", is considered one of the most important and influential texts in 20th-century musical aesthetics.<ref>{{Harv|Warner|Cox|2004|p=10}}</ref> Other examples of futurist music include [[Arthur Honegger]]'s \"[[Pacific 231]]\" (1923), which imitates the sound of a steam locomotive, [[Sergei Prokofiev|Prokofiev]]'s \"[[Le pas d'acier (Prokofiev)|The Steel Step]]\" (1926), [[Alexander Mosolov]]'s \"[[Iron Foundry]]\" (1927), and the experiments of [[Edgard Var\u00e8se]].\n\n[[Futurism (literature)|Literary futurism]] made its debut with [[Filippo Tommaso Marinetti|F.T. Marinetti]]'s ''[[Futurist Manifesto|Manifesto of Futurism]]'' (1909). Futurist poetry used unexpected combinations of images and hyper-conciseness (not to be confused with the actual length of the poem). Futurist theater works have scenes a few sentences long, use nonsensical humor, and try to discredit the deep-rooted dramatic traditions with parody. Longer literature forms, such as novels, had no place in the Futurist aesthetic, which had an obsession with speed and compression.\n\nFuturism expanded to encompass other artistic domains and ultimately included painting, sculpture, ceramics, [[graphic design]], industrial design, interior design, theatre design, textiles, drama, literature, music and architecture. In architecture, it featured a distinctive thrust towards [[rationalism]] and [[modernism]] through the use of [[advanced building materials]]. The ideals of futurism remain as significant components of modern [[Western culture]]; the emphasis on youth, speed, power and technology finding expression in much of modern commercial [[film|cinema]] and [[commercial culture]]. Futurism has produced several reactions, including the 1980s-era literary genre of [[cyberpunk]]\u2014which often treated technology with a critical eye.\n\n===Science fiction===\n[[File:Sortie de l'op\u00e9ra en l'an 2000-2.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Print (c. 1902) by [[Albert Robida]] showing a futuristic view of air travel over Paris in the year 2000 as people leave the opera.<ref>{{cite book |title= Science Fiction: Its Nature, Faults and Virtues |booktitle= The Science Fiction Novel: Imagination and Social Criticism |publisher= Advent Publishers |last= Heinlein |first= Robert A. |first2=Cyril |last2=Kornbluth |first3=Alfred |last3=Bester |first4=Robert |last4=Bloch |year= 1959 |location= University of Chicago}}</ref>]]\nMore generally, one can regard [[science fiction]] as a broad genre of [[fiction]] that often involves speculations based on current or future [[science]] or [[technology]]. Science fiction is found in books, art, television, films, games, theater, and other media. Science fiction differs from [[Fantasy literature|fantasy]] in that, within the context of the story, its imaginary elements are largely possible within scientifically established or scientifically postulated laws of nature (though ''some'' elements in a story might still be pure imaginative speculation). Settings may include the future, or alternative time-lines, and stories may depict new or speculative scientific principles (such as [[time travel]] or [[psionics]]), or new technology (such as [[nanotechnology]], [[faster-than-light]] travel or [[robot]]s). Exploring the consequences of such differences is the traditional purpose of science fiction, making it a \"literature of ideas\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n | author = Marg Gilks, Paula Fleming and Moira Allen\n | title = Science Fiction: The Literature of Ideas\n | work =\n | publisher =WritingWorld.com\n | year =2003\n | url = http://www.writing-world.com/sf/sf.shtml\n | accessdate = \n}}\n</ref>\n\nSome [[science fiction]] authors construct a postulated [[history]] of the future called a \"[[future history]]\" that provides a common background for their fiction. Sometimes authors publish a [[Chronology|timeline]] of events in their history, while other times the reader can reconstruct the order of the stories from information in the books. Some published works constitute \"future history\" in a more literal sense\u2014i.e., stories or whole books written in the style of a history book but describing events in the future. Examples include [[H.G. Wells]]' ''[[The Shape of Things to Come]]'' (1933)\u2014written in the form of a history book published in the year 2106 and in the manner of a real history book with numerous footnotes and references to the works of (mostly fictitious) prominent historians of the 20th and 21st centuries.\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [[Alternative future]]\n* [[Divination]]\n* [[List of emerging technologies]]\n* [[Neo-futurism]]\n* [[Prophecy]]\n\n===Future events===\n* [[Future of an expanding universe]]\n* [[Future of the Earth]]\n* [[Future of the Solar System]]\n* [[Timeline of the near future]]\n* [[Timeline of the far future]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Time Topics}}\n{{Science fiction}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Future}}\n[[Category:Future| ]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of time]]\n[[Category:Time]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Near future|near future events|Timeline of the near future}}\n{{Other uses|Future (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Time which has yet to occur}}\n[[File:The Last of the Spirits-John Leech, 1843.jpg|right|175px|thumb|The [[Ghost of Christmas Yet to Come]] shows [[Ebenezer Scrooge|Scrooge]] his future in [[Charles Dickens|Dickens']] ''[[A Christmas Carol]]''.]]\n{{Human history}}\n\nThe '''future''' is the [[time]] after the [[present]]. Its arrival is considered inevitable due to the existence of [[time]] and the [[laws of physics]].  Due to the apparent nature of [[reality]] and the unavoidability of the future, everything that currently [[wikt: exist|exists]] and will exist can be categorized as either permanent, meaning that it will exist forever, or temporary, meaning that it will end.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UD8TAAAAYAAJ ''Encyclop\u00e6dia of religion and ethics'']. Edinburgh: T. & T. Clark. pp. 335\u2013337.</ref> In the [[Western culture|Occidental]] view, which uses a linear conception of time, the future is the portion of the projected timeline that is anticipated to occur.<ref>Moore, C.-L. & Yamamoto, K. (1988). ''Beyond words: movement observation and analysis''. New York: Gordon and Breach. p. 57. (cf., The representation of time as a linear, unidirectional progression is a distinctly Occidental point of view.)</ref> In [[special relativity]], the future is considered [[absolute future]], or the future [[light cone]].<ref>Eddington, A. S. (1921). [https://archive.org/details/spacetimeandgra00eddigoog ''Space, time and gravitation; an outline of the general relativity theory'']. Cambridge: University Press. p. 107.</ref>\n\nIn the [[philosophy of time]], [[Philosophical presentism|presentism]] is the [[belief]] that only the present [[existence|exists]] and the future and the past are [[reality|unreal]]. Religions consider the future when they address issues such as [[karma]], [[afterlife|life after death]], and [[eschatology|eschatologies]] that study what the end of time and the end of the world will be. Religious figures such as [[prophet]]s and [[divination|diviners]] have claimed to see into the future. \nFuture studies, or [[futurology]], is the science, art, and practice of postulating possible futures. Modern practitioners stress the importance of alternative and plural futures, rather than one monolithic future, and the limitations of prediction and [[probability]], versus the creation of possible and preferable futures.\n\nThe concept of the future has been explored extensively in cultural production, including [[art]] movements and genres devoted entirely to its elucidation, such as the 20th-century movement [[futurism]].\n\n==Physics==\n[[File:World line.svg|250px|right|thumb|A visualization of the future [[light cone]] (at the top), the present, and the past light cone in 2D space.]]\n{{See also|Time in physics}}\nIn physics, time is the fourth dimension. Physicists argue that [[spacetime]] can be understood as a sort of stretchy fabric that bends due to forces such as gravity. In [[classical physics]] the future is just a half of the timeline, which is the same for all observers. In [[special relativity]] the flow of time is relative to the observer's [[frame of reference]]. The faster an observer is traveling away from a reference object, the slower that object seems to move through time. Hence, the future is not an objective notion anymore. A more modern notion is [[absolute future]], or the future [[light cone]]. While a person can move backward or forwards in the three spatial dimensions, many physicists argue you are only able to move forward in time.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.livescience.com/technology/070307_time_travel.html|title=You Can't Travel Back in Time, Scientists Say|publisher=|accessdate=31 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOne of the outcomes of Special Relativity Theory is that a person can travel into the future (but never come back) by traveling at very high speeds. While this effect is negligible under ordinary conditions, space travel at very high speeds can change the flow of time considerably. As depicted in many [[science fiction]] stories and movies (e.g. ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (2006 film)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]''), a person traveling for even a short time at near [[light speed]] will return to an Earth that is many years in the future.\n\nSome physicists claim that by using a [[wormhole]] to connect two regions of spacetime a person could theoretically travel in time. Physicist [[Michio Kaku]] points out that to power this hypothetical time machine and \"punch a hole into the fabric of space-time\", it would require the energy of a star. Another theory is that a person could travel in time with [[cosmic string]]s.\n\n==Philosophy==\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = \"The trouble with the future is that it's so much less knowable than the past.\" \n| source =&nbsp;[[John Lewis Gaddis]], ''The Landscape of History''.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Landscape of History: How Historians Map the Past |last= Gaddis|first= John Lewis|year= 2002|publisher= Oxford University Press|location= New York|isbn= 978-0-19-517157-0|pages= 56}}\n&nbsp;</ref> \n| width  = 27%\n| align  = right\n| style = padding:8px;\n}}\n\nIn the [[philosophy of time]], presentism is the [[belief]] that only the present [[existence|exists]], and the future and [[past]] are [[reality|unreal]]. Past and future \"entities\" are construed as [[logic]]al constructions or [[fictionalism|fictions]]. The opposite of presentism is '[[Eternalism (philosophy of time)|eternalism]]', which is the belief that things in the past and things yet to come exist [[eternity|eternally]]. Another view (not held by many philosophers) is sometimes called the '[[Growing block universe|growing block]]' [[theory]] of time\u2014which postulates that the past and present exist, but the future does not.<ref>{{cite book| last=Broad| first= C.D.| title= Scientific Thought| location=New York| publisher=Harcourt, Brace and Co.| year=1923| url=http://www.ditext.com/broad/st/st-con.html}}</ref>\n\nPresentism is [[wikt: compatible|compatible]] with [[Galilean relativity]], in which time is independent of space, but is probably incompatible with [[Hendrik Lorentz|Lorentz]]ian/[[Einstein]]ian relativity in conjunction with certain other philosophical [[thesis|theses]] that many find uncontroversial. [[Augustine of Hippo|Saint Augustine]] [[Research proposal|proposed]] that the present is a knife edge between the past and the future and could not contain any extended period of time.\n\nContrary to Saint Augustine, some philosophers propose that conscious experience is extended in time.  For instance, [[William James]] said that time is \"...the short duration of which we are immediately and incessantly sensible.\"{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}  Augustine proposed that God is outside of time and present for all times, in [[eternity]]. Other early philosophers who were presentists include the [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (in the tradition of [[Indian Buddhism]]). A leading scholar from the modern era on [[Buddhist philosophy]] is [[Theodor Ippolitovich Stcherbatsky|Stcherbatsky]], who has written extensively on Buddhist presentism: {{cquote|Everything past is unreal, everything future is unreal, everything imagined, absent, mental... is unreal... Ultimately real is only the present moment of physical [[wikt:efficiency|efficiency]] [i.e., [[Causality|causation]]].<ref>Vol.1 of ''Buddhist Logic'', 1962, Dover: New York. 70\u201371.</ref>}}\n\n==Psychology==\n{{unreferenced section|date=October 2018}}\n[[Human behavior]] is known to encompass anticipation of the future. Anticipatory behavior can be the result of a psychological outlook toward the future, for examples [[optimism]], [[pessimism]], and [[hope]].\n\nOptimism is an outlook on life such that one maintains a view of the world as a positive place. People would say that optimism is seeing the glass \"half full\" of water as opposed to half empty. It is the philosophical opposite of pessimism. Optimists generally believe that people and events are inherently good, so that most situations work out in the end for the best. Hope is a belief in a positive outcome related to events and circumstances in one's life. Hope implies a certain amount of despair, wanting, wishing, suffering or perseverance\u2014i.e., believing that a better or positive outcome is possible even when there is some evidence to the contrary. \"Hopefulness\" is somewhat different from optimism in that hope is an emotional state, whereas optimism is a conclusion reached through a deliberate thought pattern that leads to a positive attitude.\n\n[[Pessimism]] as stated before is the opposite of optimism. It is the tendency to see, anticipate, or emphasize only bad or undesirable outcomes, results, or problems. The word originates in Latin from Pessimus meaning worst and Malus meaning bad.\n\n==Religion==\nReligions consider the future when they address issues such as [[karma]], [[afterlife|life after death]], and [[eschatology|eschatologies]] that study what the end of time and the end of the world will be. In religion, major prophets are said to have the power to change the future.  Common religious figures have claimed to see into the future, such as minor [[prophet]]s and [[divination|diviners]].\nThe term \"afterlife\" refers to the continuation of [[existence]] of the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]], [[spirit]] or [[mind]] of a human (or animal) after physical [[death]], typically in a [[Spirituality|spiritual]] or [[ghost]]like afterworld. Deceased persons are usually believed to go to a specific region or [[planes of existence|plane of existence]] in this afterworld, often depending on the rightness of their actions during life.\n\nSome believe the afterlife includes some form of preparation for the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]] to transfer to another body ([[reincarnation]]).\nThe major views on the afterlife derive from [[religion]], [[esotericism]] and [[metaphysics]]. There are those who are skeptical of the existence of the afterlife, or believe that it is absolutely impossible, such as the [[materialism|materialist]]-reductionists, who believe that the topic is [[supernatural]], therefore does not really exist or is unknowable. In metaphysical models, [[theists]] generally, believe some sort of afterlife awaits people when they die. [[Atheism|Atheists]] generally do not believe in a life after death. Members of some generally non-theistic religions such as [[Buddhism]], tend to believe in an afterlife like [[reincarnation]] but without reference to [[God]].\n\n[[Agnosticism|Agnostics]] generally hold the position that like the existence of God, the existence of supernatural phenomena, such as souls or life after death, is unverifiable and therefore unknowable.<ref>{{cite dictionary | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/agnostic | title=agnositic | dictionary=Merriam-Webster | accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> Many religions, whether they believe in the soul's existence in another world like Christianity, Islam and many [[Paganism|pagan]] belief systems, or in reincarnation like many forms of Hinduism and Buddhism, believe that one's status in the afterlife is a reward or punishment for their conduct during life, with the exception of [[Calvinistic]] variants of [[Protestant]] Christianity, which believes one's status in the afterlife is a gift from God and cannot be earned during life.\n\n[[Eschatology]] is a part of [[theology]] and [[philosophy]] concerned with the final events in the [[history of the world]], or the ultimate [[destiny]] of [[All humanity|humanity]], commonly referred to as the end of the world. While in [[mysticism]] the phrase refers metaphorically to the end of ordinary reality and reunion with the Divine, in many traditional [[religion]]s it is taught as an actual future event [[prophecy|prophesied]] in [[sacred text]]s or [[folklore]]. More broadly, eschatology may encompass related concepts such as the [[Messiah]] or [[Messianic Age]], the [[end time]], and the [[End of Days (eschatology)|end of days]].\n\n== Grammar ==\nIn [[grammar]], actions are classified according to one of the following twelve verb tenses: past ([[past]], [[Uses of English verb forms#Past progressive|past continuous]], [[past perfect]], or [[past perfect continuous]]), present ([[present]], [[present continuous]], [[present perfect]], or [[present perfect continuous]]), or future (future, [[future continuous]], [[future perfect]], or [[future perfect continuous]]).<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> The future tense refers to actions that have not yet happened, but which are due, expected, or likely to occur in the future.<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> For example, in the sentence, \"She will walk home,\" the verb \"will walk\" is in the future tense because it refers to an action that is going to, or is likely to, happen at a point in time beyond the present.\n\nVerbs in the future continuous tense indicate actions that will happen beyond the present and will continue for a period of time.<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> In the sentence, \"She will be walking home,\" the [[verb phrase]] \"will be walking\" is in the future continuous tense because the action described is not happening now, but will happen sometime afterwards and is expected to continue happening for some time. Verbs in the future perfect tense indicate actions that will be completed at a particular point in the future.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Merriam-Webster |title=Present Perfect |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/present%20perfect |website=Merriam-Webster.com |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=27 August 2018 |format=Web |date=n.d.}}</ref> For example, the [[verb phrase]], \"will have walked,\" in the sentence, \"She will have walked home,\" is in the future perfect tense because it refers to an action that is completed as of a specific time in the future. Finally, verbs in the future perfect continuous tense combine the features of the perfect and continuous tenses, describing the future status of actions that have been happening continually from now or the past through to a particular time in the future.<ref>{{cite web |author1=(no author) |title=Verb tenses |url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/grammar/verb-tenses |website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> In the sentence, \"She will have been walking home,\" the verb phrase \"will have been walking\" is in the future perfect continuous tense because it refers to an action that the speaker anticipates will be finished in the future.\n\nAnother way to think of the various future tenses is that actions described by the future tense will be completed at an unspecified time in the future, actions described by the future continuous tense will keep happening in the future, actions described by the future perfect tense will be completed at a specific time in the future, and actions described by the future perfect continuous tense are expected to be continuing as of a specific time in the future.\n\n== Linear and cyclic culture ==\nThe linear view of time (common in [[Western thought]]) draws a stronger distinction between past and future than does the more common [[cyclic time]] of cultures such as India, where past and future can coalesce much more readily.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Ridderbos\n| first1                = Katinka\n| title                 = Time\n| url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=muoM9H8Z8o8C\n| series                = Darwin College Lectures\n| issue                 = 14\n| publisher             = Cambridge University Press\n| publication-date      = 2002\n| page                  = 2\n| isbn                  = 978-0521782937\n| accessdate            = 2015-09-03\n| quote                 = In a cyclic universe, each event that lies in the past of the present moment, also lies in its future. \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Futures studies==\n[[Image: Stanford Torus interior.jpg|thumb|right|Project of an orbital colony [[Stanford torus]], painted by Donald E. Davis]]\n[[Futures studies]] or futurology is the science, art, and practice of postulating possible, probable, and preferable futures and the worldviews and myths that underlie them. Futures studies seek to understand what is likely to continue, what is likely to change, and what is novel. Part of the discipline thus seeks a systematic and pattern-based understanding of past and present, and to determine the likelihood of future events and trends.  A key part of this process is understanding the potential future impact of decisions made by individuals, organizations, and governments.  Leaders use the results of such work to assist in decision-making.\n\n{{cquote|Take hold of the future or the future will take hold of you.<br>{{mdash}}[[Patrick Dixon]], author of ''[[Futurewise (book)|Futurewise]]''}}\nFutures is an interdisciplinary field, studying yesterday's and today's changes, and aggregating and analyzing both lay and professional strategies, and opinions with respect to tomorrow. It includes analyzing the sources, patterns, and causes of change and stability in the attempt to develop foresight and to map possible futures. Modern practitioners stress the importance of alternative and plural futures, rather than one monolithic future, and the limitations of prediction and probability, versus the creation of possible and preferable futures.\n\nThree factors usually distinguish futures studies from the research conducted by other disciplines (although all disciplines overlap, to differing degrees). First, futures studies often examines not only possible but also probable, preferable, and \"wild card\" futures. Second, futures studies typically attempts to gain a holistic or systemic view based on insights from a range of different disciplines. Third, futures studies challenges and unpacks the assumptions behind dominant and contending views of the future. The future thus is not empty but fraught with hidden assumptions.\n\nFutures studies do not generally include the work of economists who forecast movements of interest rates over the next business cycle, or of managers or investors with short-term time horizons. Most strategic planning, which develops operational plans for preferred futures with time horizons of one to three years, is also not considered futures. But plans and strategies with longer time horizons that specifically attempt to anticipate and be robust to possible future events, are part of a major subdiscipline of futures studies called strategic foresight.\n\nThe futures field also excludes those who make future predictions through professed supernatural means. At the same time, it does seek to understand the model's such groups use and the interpretations they give to these models.\n\n===Forecasting===\n{{Main|Forecasting}}\nForecasting is the process of [[Estimation|estimating]] outcomes in uncontrolled situations. Forecasting is applied in many areas, such as [[weather forecasting]], [[earthquake prediction]], [[transport planning]], and [[labour market]] planning. Due to the element of the unknown, [[risk]] and [[uncertainty]] are central to forecasting.\n\nStatistically based forecasting employs [[time series]] with [[cross-sectional data|cross-sectional]] or [[longitudinal study|longitudinal]] data. [[Econometric]] forecasting methods use the assumption that it is possible to identify the underlying factors that might influence the variable that is being forecast. If the causes are understood, projections of the influencing variables can be made and used in the forecast. Judgmental forecasting methods incorporate intuitive judgments, opinions, and probability estimates, as in the case of the [[Delphi method]], [[scenario building]], and [[simulation]]s.\n\nPrediction is similar to forecasting but is used more generally, for instance, to also include baseless claims on the future. Organized efforts to [[prediction|predict]] the future began with practices like [[astrology]], [[haruspicy]], and [[augury]]. These are all considered to be [[pseudoscience]] today, evolving from the human desire to know the future in advance.\n\nModern efforts such as [[futures studies]] attempt to predict technological and societal trends, while more ancient practices, such as weather forecasting, have benefited from [[Scientific modeling|scientific]] and [[causal model]]ling. Despite the development of [[cognition|cognitive]] instruments for the comprehension of future, the [[stochastic process|stochastic]] and [[Chaos theory|chaotic]] nature of many natural and social processes has made precise forecasting of the future elusive.\n\n==In art and culture==\n===Futurism===\n<!--\"Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Layout of building complex\" links here -->\n[[Futurism]] as an [[art movement]] originated in [[Italy]] at the beginning of the 20th century. It developed largely in [[Italy]] and in [[Russia]], although it also had adherents in other countries\u2014in England and Portugal for example. The Futurists explored every medium of art, including [[painting]], [[sculpture]], [[poetry]], [[theatre]], [[music]], [[architecture]], and even [[gastronomy]]. Futurists had passionate loathing of ideas from the past, especially political and artistic traditions. They also espoused a love of [[speed]], [[technology]], and [[violence]]. Futurists dubbed the love of the past ''[[pass\u00e9isme]]''. The car, the plane, and the industrial town were all legendary for the Futurists because they represented the technological triumph of people over [[nature]].  The ''[[Futurist Manifesto]]'' of 1909 declared: \"We will glorify war\u2014the world's only hygiene\u2014militarism, patriotism, the destructive gesture of freedom-bringers, beautiful ideas worth dying for, and scorn for woman.\"<ref name=\"futurmanifest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italianfuturism.org/manifestos/foundingmanifesto/|title=The Founding and Manifesto of Futurism|publisher=italianfuturism.org (Originally published on [[Le Figaro]], [[Paris]], February 20, 1909)}}</ref>  Though it owed much of its character and some of its ideas to [[political radicalism|radical political movements]], it had little involvement in politics until the autumn of 1913.<ref>Martin, Marianne W., p .186</ref>\n\nFuturism in Classical Music arose during this same time period. Closely identified with the central Italian Futurist movement were brother composers [[Luigi Russolo]] (1885\u20131947) and [[Antonio Russolo]] (1877\u20131942), who used instruments known as ''[[intonarumori]]''\u2014essentially [[sound box]]es used to create music out of noise. Luigi Russolo's futurist manifesto, \"[[The Art of Noises]]\", is considered one of the most important and influential texts in 20th-century musical aesthetics.<ref>{{Harv|Warner|Cox|2004|p=10}}</ref> Other examples of futurist music include [[Arthur Honegger]]'s \"[[Pacific 231]]\" (1923), which imitates the sound of a steam locomotive, [[Sergei Prokofiev|Prokofiev]]'s \"[[Le pas d'acier (Prokofiev)|The Steel Step]]\" (1926), [[Alexander Mosolov]]'s \"[[Iron Foundry]]\" (1927), and the experiments of [[Edgard Var\u00e8se]].\n\n[[Futurism (literature)|Literary futurism]] made its debut with [[Filippo Tommaso Marinetti|F.T. Marinetti]]'s ''[[Futurist Manifesto|Manifesto of Futurism]]'' (1909). Futurist poetry used unexpected combinations of images and hyper-conciseness (not to be confused with the actual length of the poem). Futurist theater works have scenes a few sentences long, use nonsensical humor, and try to discredit the deep-rooted dramatic traditions with parody. Longer literature forms, such as novels, had no place in the Futurist aesthetic, which had an obsession with speed and compression.\n\nFuturism expanded to encompass other artistic domains and ultimately included painting, sculpture, ceramics, [[graphic design]], industrial design, interior design, theatre design, textiles, drama, literature, music and architecture. In architecture, it featured a distinctive thrust towards [[rationalism]] and [[modernism]] through the use of [[advanced building materials]]. The ideals of futurism remain as significant components of modern [[Western culture]]; the emphasis on youth, speed, power and technology finding expression in much of modern commercial [[film|cinema]] and [[commercial culture]]. Futurism has produced several reactions, including the 1980s-era literary genre of [[cyberpunk]]\u2014which often treated technology with a critical eye.\n\n===Science fiction===\n[[File:Sortie de l'op\u00e9ra en l'an 2000-2.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Print (c. 1902) by [[Albert Robida]] showing a futuristic view of air travel over Paris in the year 2000 as people leave the opera.<ref>{{cite book |title= Science Fiction: Its Nature, Faults and Virtues |booktitle= The Science Fiction Novel: Imagination and Social Criticism |publisher= Advent Publishers |last= Heinlein |first= Robert A. |first2=Cyril |last2=Kornbluth |first3=Alfred |last3=Bester |first4=Robert |last4=Bloch |year= 1959 |location= University of Chicago}}</ref>]]\nMore generally, one can regard [[science fiction]] as a broad genre of [[fiction]] that often involves speculations based on current or future [[science]] or [[technology]]. Science fiction is found in books, art, television, films, games, theater, and other media. Science fiction differs from [[Fantasy literature|fantasy]] in that, within the context of the story, its imaginary elements are largely possible within scientifically established or scientifically postulated laws of nature (though ''some'' elements in a story might still be pure imaginative speculation). Settings may include the future, or alternative time-lines, and stories may depict new or speculative scientific principles (such as [[time travel]] or [[psionics]]), or new technology (such as [[nanotechnology]], [[faster-than-light]] travel or [[robot]]s). Exploring the consequences of such differences is the traditional purpose of science fiction, making it a \"literature of ideas\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n | author = Marg Gilks, Paula Fleming and Moira Allen\n | title = Science Fiction: The Literature of Ideas\n | work =\n | publisher =WritingWorld.com\n | year =2003\n | url = http://www.writing-world.com/sf/sf.shtml\n | accessdate = \n}}\n</ref>\n\nSome [[science fiction]] authors construct a postulated [[history]] of the future called a \"[[future history]]\" that provides a common background for their fiction. Sometimes authors publish a [[Chronology|timeline]] of events in their history, while other times the reader can reconstruct the order of the stories from information in the books. Some published works constitute \"future history\" in a more literal sense\u2014i.e., stories or whole books written in the style of a history book but describing events in the future. Examples include [[H.G. Wells]]' ''[[The Shape of Things to Come]]'' (1933)\u2014written in the form of a history book published in the year 2106 and in the manner of a real history book with numerous footnotes and references to the works of (mostly fictitious) prominent historians of the 20th and 21st centuries.\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [[Alternative future]]\n* [[Divination]]\n* [[List of emerging technologies]]\n* [[Neo-futurism]]\n* [[Prophecy]]\n\n===Future events===\n* [[Future of an expanding universe]]\n* [[Future of the Earth]]\n* [[Future of the Solar System]]\n* [[Timeline of the near future]]\n* [[Timeline of the far future]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Time Topics}}\n{{Science fiction}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Future}}\n[[Category:Future| ]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of time]]\n[[Category:Time]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:6f40:4bf0:f8c8:44f5:b3bf:9471", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePhysics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Future"}
{"title_page": "2018 British Columbia electoral reform referendum", "text_new": "{{Short description|referendum on British Columbia's voting system}}\n{{Infobox multichoice referendum \n| name        = British Columbia electoral reform referendum \n| map         = British_Columbia_Electoral_Reform_Referendum_2018_-_Question_1_Results_by_Riding.svg\n| mapcaption = Question 1 results by electoral district (green: FPTP; red: PR)\n| mapdivision  = electoral district\n| title       = Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections?\n| location    = [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| date        = {{Start date|2018|10|22}} \u2013 {{End date|2018|12|7}}\n| choice1 = The current First Past the Post voting system\n| percentage1 = 61.3\n| choice2 = A proportional representation voting system\n| percentage2 = 38.7\n| status = complete\n}}\n\nA referendum on [[electoral reform]] took place by [[postal ballot|mail-in ballot]] between October 22 and December 7, 2018, in the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[British Columbia]]. This was British Columbia's third referendum on electoral reform since 2005.\n\nVoters were asked two questions: first, what electoral system should be used to determine election results\u2014the existing [[first-past-the-post]] (FPTP) system or a [[proportional representation]] (PR) system; and second, what type of proportional voting system should be used if PR is chosen. In the second question, voters were asked to rank three proportional representation voting systems: [[dual-member proportional representation]], [[mixed-member proportional representation]], and [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]].\n\nThe referendum fulfilled an election commitment by the [[British Columbia New Democratic Party]] (NDP) during the 2017 election. Their platform promised a referendum and that the government would actively campaign for electoral reform.\n\nResults were released by [[Elections BC]] on December 20, 2018. British Columbians voted in favour of maintaining the first-past-the-post voting system rather than switching to a proportional representation voting system.\n\n==Background==\nBC has a long history of changing its electoral system. For BC's first election in 1871, the majority of ridings were elected using an \"at large\" system. This is the way city councillors are elected in BC to this day: a voter gets as many votes as there were people to be elected in the riding.<ref name=1871-1986>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC|Elections British Columbia]] |title=Electoral History of British Columbia 1871\u20131986 |date=1988 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613200446/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf# |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOver its history, BC modified its electoral system at least 15 times without a referendum.<ref name=1871-1986 /> It previously used an [[Instant-runoff voting|alternative voting system]] in the [[1952 British Columbia general election|1952 provincial election]] before abolishing it and reestablishing the previous mix of \"at large\" and first-past-the-post.<ref name=\"pdennis\">{{Cite book |title=The politics of voting : reforming Canada's electoral system |last=Pilon |first=Dennis |date=2007 |publisher=Emond Montgomery Publications |isbn=9781552392362 |location=Toronto |oclc=150223313}}</ref>{{rp|81\u201382}}<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC|Elections British Columbia]] |title=Electoral History of British Columbia 1871\u20131986 |date=1988 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf |access-date=21 June 2018 |pages=231\u2013232 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613200446/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/1871-1986_ElectoralHistoryofBC.pdf# |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first BC election done entirely under first-past-the-post came in 1991, after the last \"at-large\" voting districts had been abolished.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|76}}<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC]] |title=Electoral History of B.C. |date=2018 |url=http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/ |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626030841/http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/# |archive-date=26 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The multi-member at-large ridings were abolished after the 1986 election due to a Supreme Court of Canada ruling that found them unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web |last=[[Elections BC]] |title=Electoral History of B.C. |date=2018 |url=http://elections.bc.ca/resources/learning-about-elections/electoral-history-of-bc/}}</ref>\n\n\n===Previous referendums===\nBefore the [[2001 British Columbia general election|2001 provincial election]], the [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal Party]] committed to appoint a [[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|Citizens' Assembly]] to investigate electoral reform, hold consultations, and prepare a report recommending whether a different [[electoral system]] should be adopted.<ref name=CAReport>{{cite web |title=Making Every Vote Count: The Case for Electoral Reform in British Columbia |url=http://www.citizensassembly.bc.ca:80/resources/final_report.pdf |date=December 2004 |access-date=15 June 2018 |author=[[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|British Columbia Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform]] |publisher=Government of British Columbia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050513192722/http://www.citizensassembly.bc.ca/resources/final_report.pdf# |archive-date=13 May 2005}}</ref> The commitment was driven in part by the anomalous provincial election result in [[1996 British Columbia general election|1996]], in which the BC New Democratic Party won reelection as a majority government with 39.5% of the vote and 39 seats, despite gaining a 3% smaller share of the popular vote than the Liberals at 41.8%, which translated into 33 Liberal seats.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|90\u201391}} In December 2004, the Assembly released its report recommending that the province adopt [[BC-STV]], a BC-specific variant of the [[single transferable vote]] (STV) system.<ref name=CAReport /> On May 17, 2005, a [[2005 British Columbia electoral reform referendum|referendum]] was held in conjunction with the [[2005 British Columbia general election|2005 general election]], in which voters were asked whether the province should adopt the recommendation of the Assembly to replace the first-past-the-post electoral system with BC-STV, or maintain the current system. While 57.7% of the electorate voted in favour of BC-STV, including a majority of voters in 77 of 79 ridings, its support failed to reach the 60% threshold set by the government and it was not adopted.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elections BC |title=Statement of Votes \u2013 Referendum on Electoral Reform |date=May 17, 2005 |page=9 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/SOV-2005-ReferendumOnElectoralReform.pdf |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220152639/http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/SOV-2005-ReferendumOnElectoralReform.pdf# |archive-date=20 February 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2005 referendum, British Columbia held [[2009 British Columbia electoral reform referendum|a second referendum]] on electoral reform in conjunction with the [[2009 British Columbia general election|provincial election]] on May 12, 2009. It was the most recent referendum on electoral reform that has been held in British Columbia. As in 2005, voters in 2009 were asked to provide their opinions on the BC-STV electoral system proposed by the [[Citizens' Assembly on Electoral Reform (British Columbia)|British Columbia Citizen's Assembly on Electoral Reform]] to ensure more proportional representation in the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|provincial Legislative Assembly]]. British Columbians were asked which electoral system should be used to elect legislators: the existing first-past-the-post electoral system or the proposed BC-STV system.\n\nThe adoption of BC-STV in the 2009 referendum was defeated, with 60.9% voting against the reform and 39.09% of voters supporting the change.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elections BC |title=Statement of Votes \u2013 Referendum on Electoral Reform |date=May 12, 2009 |page=20 |url=http://www.elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/2009Ref/2009-Ref-SOV.pdf |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423200639/http://elections.bc.ca/docs/rpt/2009Ref/2009-Ref-SOV.pdf# |archive-date=23 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Intervening federal developments===\nDuring the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 federal election]], [[Justin Trudeau]] and the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] campaigned on the promise that it would be the last federal election under the first-past-the-post electoral system. The party's platform stated that a Liberal government would form an all-party Parliamentary committee, and introduce legislation within 18 months enacting electoral reform.<ref>{{cite web |title=Electoral reform |url=https://www.liberal.ca/realchange/electoral-reform/ |website=Real Change |publisher=Liberal Party of Canada |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621194408/https://www.liberal.ca/realchange/electoral-reform/# |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"2part-question\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/b-c-electoral-reform-referendum-includes-two-part-ballot-question|title=B.C. electoral reform referendum includes two-part ballot question|last=Meissner|first=Dirk|date=May 30, 2018|work=[[The National Post]]|access-date=4 June 2018}}</ref> On December 1, 2016, the [[Canadian House of Commons Special Committee on Electoral Reform|House of Commons of Canada Special Committee on Electoral Reform]] released its report recommending Canada hold a referendum to adopt a proportional representation voting system for federal elections.<ref name=\"fed-report\">{{cite report |author=Special Committee on Electoral Reform |date=December 1, 2016 |title=Strengthening Democracy in Canada: Principles, Process and Public Engagement for Electoral Reform |url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?DocId=8655791&Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=42&Ses=1 |publisher=Parliament of Canada |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408092349/http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=e&Mode=1&Parl=42&Ses=1&DocId=8655791# |archive-date=8 April 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Several months later, the government announced that it was no longer pursuing electoral reform.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stone |first=Laura |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-abandons-electoral-reform/article33855925/ |title=Trudeau abandons electoral reform, breaking key campaign promise |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |access-date=6 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205160959/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-abandons-electoral-reform/article33855925/# |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Joanna |title=Trudeau abandons promise for electoral reform |url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/trudeau-abandons-promise-for-electoral-reform/ |access-date=21 June 2018 |work=Maclean's |agency=The Canadian Press |date=February 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209174029/http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/trudeau-abandons-promise-for-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=9 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Origin of third referendum===\nDuring the [[2017 British Columbia general election|2017 provincial election]], both the NDP and the [[Green Party of British Columbia|Green Party]] campaigned for PR and included the policy in their election platforms.<ref name=\"NDPplatform\">{{cite web |title=Platform 2017 |url=https://action.bcndp.ca/page/-/bcndp/docs/BC-NDP-Platform-2017.pdf |website=bcndp.ca |publisher=BC NDP |access-date=30 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510162021/https://action.bcndp.ca/page/-/bcndp/docs/BC-NDP-Platform-2017.pdf# |archive-date=10 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-election-aftermath-electoral-reform-1.4122921 |title=B.C. parties leave door open to electoral reform without a referendum |last=Omand |first=Geordon |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 18, 2017 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604094829/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-election-aftermath-electoral-reform-1.4122921# |archive-date=4 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=BC Green Party |title=Change You Can Count On: Platform 2017 |date=2017 |url=https://www.bcgreens.ca/platform |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140957/https://www.bcgreens.ca/platform# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 29, 2017, approximately three weeks after the election resulted in a [[British Columbia Liberal Party|BC Liberal]] [[minority government]], the NDP and Green caucuses signed a [[Confidence and supply|supply and confidence]] agreement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-ndp-green-agreement-1.4136539 |title=B.C. Green Party agrees to support NDP in the legislature |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 29, 2017 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180605094150/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-ndp-green-agreement-1.4136539# |archive-date=5 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The agreement included a section on PR, in which the parties agreed to put the issue to a referendum and that both parties would actively campaign for PR in the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |last=BC NDP Caucus |title=2017 Confidence and Supply Agreement between the BC Green Caucus and the BC New Democrat Caucus |date=May 30, 2017 |url=http://bcndpcaucus.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2017/05/BC-Green-BC-NDP-Agreement_vf-May-29th-2017.pdf |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712183901/http://bcndpcaucus.ca/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2017/05/BC-Green-BC-NDP-Agreement_vf-May-29th-2017.pdf# |archive-date=12 July 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/whats-ahead-for-bc-politics-after-the-ndp-green-partyagreement/article35160029/ |title=The road ahead for B.C. politics |last=Hipolito |first=Chad |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=May 31, 2018 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813154305/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/whats-ahead-for-bc-politics-after-the-ndp-green-partyagreement/article35160029/# |archive-date=13 August 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On June 22, 2017, the Liberal government tabled its [[throne speech]], adopting the opposition parties' policy to hold a third referendum on electoral reform.<ref>{{cite web |last=Meissner |first=Dirk |title=B.C. Throne Speech: Clark's Liberals Promise Electoral Reform Referendum, Sales Tax Cut |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/06/22/b-c-throne-speech-clarks-liberals-promise-electoral-reform-re_a_22583513/ |access-date=11 June 2018 |date=June 23, 2017 |work=[[Huffington Post Canada]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141218/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2017/06/22/b-c-throne-speech-clarks-liberals-promise-electoral-reform-re_a_22583513/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Speech from the Throne |url=https://www.leg.bc.ca/parliamentary-business/legislation-debates-proceedings/41st-parliament/1st-session/throne-speech |access-date=11 June 2018 |date=June 22, 2017 |publisher=[[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141507/https://www.leg.bc.ca/parliamentary-business/legislation-debates-proceedings/41st-parliament/1st-session/throne-speech# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On June 29, 2017, the BC Liberal government was defeated in a [[confidence and supply|confidence vote]]. [[Lieutenant Governor of British Columbia|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Judith Guichon]] then invited the NDP to form a minority government with Green support.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McElroy |first1=Justin |title=NDP Leader John Horgan to be next premier of British Columbia |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/horgan-government-guichon-2017-1.4185204 |access-date=30 June 2017 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630112221/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/horgan-government-guichon-2017-1.4185204# |archive-date=30 June 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> On November 30, 2017, the ''Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Act'' was passed into law.<ref>{{Cite canlaw |short title=Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Act |abbr=SBC |year=2017 |chapter=22 |link=http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/complete/statreg/17022_01}}</ref> It required the referendum to be held and authorized [[Executive Council of British Columbia|Cabinet]] to make various regulations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Justine |title=B.C. NDP, Greens flex partnership with swath of new policy achievements |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/bc-ndp-greens-flex-partnership-with-swath-of-new-policy-achievements/article37158183/ |date=November 30, 2017 |access-date=23 June 2018 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418220125/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/british-columbia/bc-ndp-greens-flex-partnership-with-swath-of-new-policy-achievements/article37158183/# |archive-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Consultation and implementation==\nBetween November 2017 and February 2018, [[Attorney General]] [[David Eby]] conducted a public consultation entitled \"How We Vote\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Meissner |first=Dirk |title=B.C. New Democrats invite public electoral reform vote; Liberals cry foul |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-new-democrats-invite-public-electoral-reform-vote-liberals-cry-foul |date=November 23, 2017 |access-date=7 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142419/http://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-new-democrats-invite-public-electoral-reform-vote-liberals-cry-foul# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 30, 2018, he released the report on the consultation and recommendations concerning how the referendum process should be conducted.<ref name=\"2018report\">{{cite web |last=Eby |first=David |date=May 30, 2018 |title=How We Vote 2018 Electoral Reform Referendum: Report and Recommendations of the Attorney General |url=https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/05/How-We-Vote-2018-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Report-and-Recommendations-of-the-Attorney-General.pdf |publisher=Government of British Columbia |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831060310/https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/05/How-We-Vote-2018-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Report-and-Recommendations-of-the-Attorney-General.pdf# |archive-date=31 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Tyee?s\">{{cite web |url=https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/30/Eby-Proposed-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Questions/ |title=Eby Unveils Proposed Electoral Reform Referendum Questions |last=MacLeod |first=Andrew |work=[[The Tyee]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142804/https://thetyee.ca/News/2018/05/30/Eby-Proposed-Electoral-Reform-Referendum-Questions/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Eagland |first=Nick |title=New Zealand gives B.C. a lesson on proportional representation |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/new-zealand-gives-b-c-a-lesson-on-proportional-representation |date=June 4, 2018 |access-date=6 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609041248/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/new-zealand-gives-b-c-a-lesson-on-proportional-representation# |archive-date=9 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Cabinet accepted the recommendations shortly thereafter, in early June.<ref name=\"PremierStatement\">{{cite web |author=Office of the Premier |title=Premier's statement on recommendations for proportional representation referendum |date=June 7, 2018 |url=https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2018PREM0083-001137 |access-date=7 June 2018 |publisher=Government of British Columbia |type=Press release |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141900/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2018PREM0083-001137# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Fletcher |first=Tom |title=B.C. cabinet approves multiple-choice voting referendum |url=https://www.theprogress.com/news/b-c-cabinet-approves-multiple-choice-voting-referendum/ |access-date=7 June 2018 |date=June 7, 2018 |publisher=[[Black Press]] |work=The Chilliwack Progress |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612122653/https://www.theprogress.com/news/b-c-cabinet-approves-multiple-choice-voting-referendum/# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later in June, Vote PR BC launched their campaign for proportional representation, canvassing in cities across the province.<ref>{{cite web |last=Grauer |first=Perrin |title=Campaign to change B.C. voting system hits the streets, with Ontario election in mind |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/06/10/campaign-to-change-bc-voting-system-hits-the-streets-with-ontario-election-in-mind.html |date=June 10, 2018 |access-date=11 June 2018 |work=[[StarMetro (newspaper)|StarMetro Vancouver]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140600/https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/06/10/campaign-to-change-bc-voting-system-hits-the-streets-with-ontario-election-in-mind.html# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ryan |first=Denise |title=Canvassers take case for B.C. electoral reform to commuters |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/canvassers-take-case-for-b-c-electoral-reform-to-commuters |date=June 10, 2018 |access-date=11 June 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140431/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/canvassers-take-case-for-b-c-electoral-reform-to-commuters# |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Elections BC]] reviewed the referendum questions in June. On June 18, Chief Electoral Officer Anton Boegman wrote to the [[Speaker of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|Speaker of the Legislative Assembly]] advising that in his view both questions were simple and clear enough for voters to understand. He also made recommendations for small changes to the questions.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boegman |first=Anton |title=Letter to the Speaker of the Legislative Assembly |url=http://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/REF-2018-LTR-CEO-speaker-response.pdf |date=June 18, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=[[Elections BC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619214100/http://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/REF-2018-LTR-CEO-speaker-response.pdf# |archive-date=19 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Press Progress |title=Elections BC Just Blew a Giant Hole in the Big Money Campaign Attacking Electoral Reform |url=https://pressprogress.ca/elections-bc-just-blew-a-giant-hole-in-the-big-money-campaign-attacking-electoral-reform/ |date=June 19, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=Press Progress |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001245/https://pressprogress.ca/elections-bc-just-blew-a-giant-hole-in-the-big-money-campaign-attacking-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=20 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  On June 22, 2018, the government released the regulations governing the referendum.<ref name=\"regulation\">{{cite web |url=https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/06/ReferendumRegulation2018.pdf |title=Electoral Reform Referendum 2018 Regulation, Reg. 313/2018 |date=June 22, 2018 |access-date=23 June 2018 |work=govTogetherBC |publisher=Government of British Columbia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623210203/https://engage.gov.bc.ca/app/uploads/sites/271/2018/06/ReferendumRegulation2018.pdf |archive-date=23 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The regulations adopted the changes to the question proposed by the Chief Electoral Officer, and set down other rules governing the campaign.<ref>{{cite web |last=[[The Canadian Press]]|title=Electoral reform vote in B.C. includes $500,000 each for pro and con groups |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-electoral-reform-vote-in-bc-includes-500000-each-for-pro-and-con/|date=June 22, 2018 |access-date=23 June 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Little|first=Simon|title=B.C. lays out rules for fall referendum on changing the way politicians are elected|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4292443/proportional-representation-referendum-rules/|date=June 22, 2018|access-date=23 June 2018|work=[[Global News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623023255/https://globalnews.ca/news/4292443/proportional-representation-referendum-rules/#|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===ICBA lawsuit===\n\nOn June 28, 2018, the Independent Contractors and Business Association (ICBA)\u2014a lobby group for the construction industry\u2014 filed a lawsuit seeking an injunction to stop the referendum, or alternatively, to strike down the campaign financing rules governing the referendum.<ref>{{cite web |title=About ICBA |url=https://icba.ca/about-icba/ |access-date=29 June 2018 |publisher=Independent Contractors and Business Association |website=icba.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629211710/https://icba.ca/about-icba/# |archive-date=29 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=LawsuitFiled>{{cite web|last=Mulgrew|first=Ian|title=Injunction sought to halt B.C. proportional representation vote|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/injunction-sought-to-halt-b-c-proportional-representation-vote|date=June 29, 2018|access-date=29 June 2018|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629024007/http://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/injunction-sought-to-halt-b-c-proportional-representation-vote#|archive-date=29 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The lawsuit contains various complaints about the process, the referendum, and the systems on the ballot.<ref name=LawsuitFiled /> In response, NDP MLA [[Bob D'Eith]] called the lawsuit an attempt to stop people from having a choice in their electoral system, and said ICBA does not want \"ordinary people to have a stronger voice in the elections and I think they're desperate to hang on to the status quo\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Kretzel|first=Lasia|title=ICBA, Union seek injunction on proportional representation referendum|url=https://www.news1130.com/2018/06/29/icba-union-seek-injunction-proportional-representation-referendum/|date=June 29, 2018|access-date=1 July 2018|work=[[News 1130]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701165030/https://www.news1130.com/2018/06/29/icba-union-seek-injunction-proportional-representation-referendum/#|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Attorney General of British Columbia|Ministry of the Attorney General]] is defending the legislation in court.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bains|first=Camille|title=B.C. referendum campaign launches as groups file petition to stop process|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bc-referendum-campaign-launches-as-groups-file-petition-to-stop/|date=July 1, 2018|access-date=2 July 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704225722/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bc-referendum-campaign-launches-as-groups-file-petition-to-stop/#|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The official campaign began July 1, 2018.<ref name=\"regulation\" />\n\nOn July 17, 2018, ICBA's court application for an early trial date was dismissed by Justice Miriam Gropper of the [[British Columbia Supreme Court]], in order to allow the government time to respond. Following the hearing, ICBA's lawyer, Peter Gall, told reporters ICBA would be seeking an interim injunction.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mulgrew|first=Ian|title=B.C. electoral system referendum foes lose first round|url=https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-electoral-system-referendum-foes-lose-first-round|date=July 18, 2018|access-date=19 July 2018|work=[[Vancouver Sun]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718205834/https://vancouversun.com/news/politics/b-c-electoral-system-referendum-foes-lose-first-round#|archive-date=18 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, ICBA filed an application seeking an interim injunction to halt campaign financing rules and prevent ballots from being counted. The application was heard by Justice Gropper on August 7. In her decision handed down several weeks later, she dismissed the application calling ICBA's allegations about the referendum \"rhetoric\", \"conjecture\" and \"exaggeration\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Fraser |first=Keith |title=Judge refuses to stop B.C.'s referendum on proportional representation voting system |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/judge-refuses-to-stop-b-c-s-referendum-on-proportional-representation-voting-system |date=August 28, 2018 |access-date=28 August 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829013223/https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/judge-refuses-to-stop-b-c-s-referendum-on-proportional-representation-voting-system# |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ball |first=David |title=Judge quashes attempt to halt mailing of ballots for B.C.'s referendum on electoral reform |url=https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/08/28/judge-quashes-attempt-to-halt-mailing-of-ballots-for-bcs-referendum-on-electoral-reform.html |date=August 28, 2018 |access-date=29 August 2018 |work=[[StarMetro (newspaper)|The Star Vancouver]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829073738/https://www.thestar.com/vancouver/2018/08/28/judge-quashes-attempt-to-halt-mailing-of-ballots-for-bcs-referendum-on-electoral-reform.html# |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite CanLII |litigants=ICBA v British Columbia |year=2018 |court=bcsc |num=1597 |courtname=auto}}</ref> In mid-September, the ICBA announced that they will be seeking leave to appeal Justice Gropper's ruling on the interim injunction.<ref>{{cite web |last=Yuzda |first=Liza |title=ICBA seeking appeal on proportional representation referendum injunction request |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4446641/icba-seeking-appeal-on-proportional-representation-referendum-injunction-request/ |date=September 13, 2018 |access-date=13 September 2018 |work=[[Global News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913211133/https://globalnews.ca/news/4446641/icba-seeking-appeal-on-proportional-representation-referendum-injunction-request/# |archive-date=13 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> That same month, the [[British Columbia Government and Service Employees' Union]] was granted [[Intervention (law)|intervenor status]] by the court, siding against the ICBA.<ref>{{cite web |last=Macdonald |first=Gord |title=BCGEU joins legal fight over proportional representation referendum |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4495631/bcgeu-legal-fight-proportional-representation-referendum/ |date=September 28, 2018 |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=[[Global News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929113346/https://globalnews.ca/news/4495631/bcgeu-legal-fight-proportional-representation-referendum/# |archive-date=29 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe appeal of Justice Gropper's judgement concerning the interim injunction was heard on November 2. Justice Fitch of the [[British Columbia Court of Appeal]] dismissed the appeal, finding that there was no merit to the ICBA's argument.<ref>{{cite CanLII |litigants=ICBA v British Columbia |year=2018 |court=bcca |num=429 |courtname=auto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Top B.C. court rejects group's attempt to stop electoral reform referendum |url=https://theprovince.com/news/local-news/top-court-rejects-groups-attempt-to-stop-b-c-electoral-reform-referendum/wcm/be8876e2-5e41-4e4c-a6ce-cce680bbc313 |date=November 2, 2018 |access-date=2 November 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103003643/https://theprovince.com/news/local-news/top-court-rejects-groups-attempt-to-stop-b-c-electoral-reform-referendum/wcm/be8876e2-5e41-4e4c-a6ce-cce680bbc313# |archive-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Ballot structure and details==\nVoters were asked two questions in the referendum. The first revolved around what electoral system should be used to determine election results: the existing first-past-the-post system or a proportional representation system. The second question explored what type of proportional voting system should be used if PR is chosen. This involved voters ranking three proportional representation voting systems: [[dual-member proportional representation]], [[mixed-member proportional representation]], and [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]].<ref name=\"2part-question\" /><ref name=announcement>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-question-eby-1.4683919 |title=B.C. to choose between 4 systems for electoral reform referendum |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604094840/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-reform-referendum-question-eby-1.4683919# |archive-date=4 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"systems\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/pr-electoral-reform-questions-1.4688604 |title=Know your voting systems: three types of electoral reform on B.C.'s ballot |last=McElroy |first=Justin |work=[[CBC News]] |date=June 2, 2018 |access-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603182847/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/pr-electoral-reform-questions-1.4688604# |archive-date=3 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*Question 1: Which system should British Columbia use for provincial elections? (Vote for only one.)\n**The current First Past the Post voting system\n**A proportional representation voting system\n*Question 2: If British Columbia adopts a proportional representation voting system, which of the following voting systems do you prefer? (Rank in order of preference. You may choose to support one, two or all three of the systems.)\n**Dual-member proportional (DMP)\n**Mixed-member proportional (MMP)\n**Rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP)\n\n==Proportional voting systems on the ballot==\nThe referendum asked voters to rank three proportional representation voting systems in order of preference: Voters ranked one, two, or all three systems.<ref name=\"2018report\" />\n* [[dual-member proportional representation]] (DMP)\n* [[mixed-member proportional representation]] (MMP)\n* [[rural\u2013urban proportional representation]] (RUP)\n\n===Dual-member proportional (DMP)===\nDual-member proportional is an electoral system designed to produce proportional election results across a region by electing two [[legislator|representatives]] in each of the region's [[electoral district|districts]].<ref name=\"dmpreport\">{{cite web |url=https://dmpforcanada.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/dmp-report-updated-april-4-2016.pdf |title=Dual-Member Mixed Proportional: A New Electoral System for Canada |author=Sean Graham |date=April 4, 2016 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020142244/https://dmpforcanada.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/dmp-report-updated-april-4-2016.pdf# |archive-date=20 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assembly.pe.ca/sittings/2015fall/reports/23_1_2015-27-11-report.pdf |title=Recommendations in Response to the White Paper on Democratic Renewal |author=PEI Special Committee on Democratic Renewal |date=November 27, 2015 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822171727/http://www.assembly.pe.ca/sittings/2015fall/reports/23_1_2015-27-11-report.pdf# |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first seat in every district is awarded to the candidate who receives the most votes, similar to first-past-the-post voting. The second seat is awarded to one of the remaining district candidates so that proportionality is achieved across the region, using a calculation that aims to award parties their seats in the districts where they had their strongest performances.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/dual-member-proportional-dmp/ |title=Dual Member Proportional (DMP) |website=elections.bc.ca |publisher=Elections BC |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093854/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/dual-member-proportional-dmp/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDMP was invented in 2013 by a [[University of Alberta]] mathematics student named Sean Graham.<ref name=\"DmpErreMeeting\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/ERRE/meeting-33/evidence |title=Meeting No. 33 Evidence |author=[[Canadian House of Commons Special Committee on Electoral Reform]] |date=29 September 2016 |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618102546/https://www.ourcommons.ca/DocumentViewer/en/42-1/ERRE/meeting-33/evidence# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> The system was intended as a possible replacement for first-past-the-post voting in [[Elections in Canada|Canadian national and provincial elections]]. Whereas campaigns to adopt MMP representation or the single transferable vote had recently been defeated in a number of [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian provinces]] (such as the 2005 and 2009 British Columbia referendums, the [[2005 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|2005 Prince Edward Island referendum]], and the [[2007 Ontario electoral reform referendum|2007 Ontario referendum]]), the intent behind DMP was to gain broader acceptance by retaining salient features of first-past-the-post voting. These features include a one-vote ballot, relatively small districts (compared with STV), and a single tier of local representatives (in contrast to MMP).<ref name=\"DmpMediaEndorse\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/opinion/editorials/editorial-we-endorse-dmp-option-in-plebiscite-111292/ |title=Editorial: We endorse DMP option in plebiscite |author=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 29, 2016 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618102408/http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/opinion/editorials/editorial-we-endorse-dmp-option-in-plebiscite-111292/# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Mixed-member proportional===\nMixed-member proportional is a [[mixed electoral system]] in which voters get two votes: one to decide the [[legislator|representative]] for their single-seat [[electoral district|constituency]], and one for a political party. Seats in the legislature are filled firstly by candidates in local ridings, and secondly, by party candidates based on the percentage of nationwide or region-wide votes that each party received.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/mixed-member-proportional-mmp/ |title=Mixed Member Proportional (MMP) |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |website=elections.bc.ca |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093857/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/mixed-member-proportional-mmp/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, MMP was recommended by the [[Law Commission of Canada]] to be adopted for federal elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://publications.gc.ca/collections/Collection/J31-61-2004E.pdf |title=Voting Counts: Electoral Reform for Canada |author=[[Law Commission of Canada]] |date=2004 |publisher=[[Minister of Public Services and Procurement|Minister of Public Works and Government Services]] |access-date=19 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020142238/http://publications.gc.ca/collections/Collection/J31-61-2004E.pdf# |archive-date=20 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=ElectoralGame /> In 2007, Ontario held a [[2007 Ontario electoral reform referendum|provincial referendum]] to adopt the system, which failed to pass.<ref name=ElectoralGame>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/ontario-election-electoral-system-alternatives-1.4709074 |title=The electoral game: What would Ontario results look like under a different voting system? |last1=Ouellet |first1=Val\u00e9rie |last2=Dubinsky |first2=Zach |date=June 16, 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618183146/http://www.cbc.ca/news/ontario-election-electoral-system-alternatives-1.4709074# |archive-date=18 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, [[Prince Edward Island]] (PEI) voted to adopt MMP in a [[2016 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|non-binding referendum]].<ref name=\"cbc results\">{{cite news |last1=Bradley |first1=Susan |title=P.E.I. plebiscite results favour mixed member proportional representation |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/mixed-member-proportional-representation-in-plebiscite-1.3840172 |accessdate=8 November 2016 |work=CBC News |date=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129004505/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/mixed-member-proportional-representation-in-plebiscite-1.3840172# |archive-date=29 November 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> PEI held [[2019 Prince Edward Island electoral reform referendum|another referendum]] on the issue during the 2019 provincial election and narrowly voted against MMP.<ref>{{cite news |title=P.E.I. voters split on electoral reform |url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/news/pei-election/pei-voters-split-on-electoral-reform-304782/ |last=Smith |first=Katie |accessdate=April 24, 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=April 23, 2019 |location=Charlottetown, PEI |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-referendum-act-passes-legislature-1.4703182 |title=Much-amended P.E.I. referendum legislation passes |last=CBC News |date=June 12, 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=13 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613171020/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/pei-referendum-act-passes-legislature-1.4703182# |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA form of MMP is used for national elections in [[Electoral system of New Zealand#MMP in New Zealand|New Zealand]] and Germany, and in the United Kingdom for elections to the [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved parliaments]] of [[Elections in Scotland#Scottish Parliament|Scotland]] and Wales (where the system is referred to as the [[Additional Member System]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/new-zealand-democracy-1.4720787|title=Why New Zealand's former prime minister believes proportional representation works better |last=Humphrey|first=Matt|date=June 25, 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fairvote.ca/mixed-member-proportional/ |title=Mixed Member Proportional |author=[[Fair Vote Canada]] |date=2018 |work=Fair Vote Canada |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724151104/https://www.fairvote.ca/mixed-member-proportional/# |archive-date=24 July 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP)===\n[[File:Preferential ballot.svg|thumb|Simplified example of an STV ranked ballot used in an urban or semi-urban area under rural\u2013urban proportional (RUP). RUP is the only system that lets voters rank individual candidates in order of preference.]]\nRural\u2013urban proportional is a hybrid-proportional system designed by [[Fair Vote Canada]] to meet the challenges of Canada's geography.<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\">{{cite web|last=[[Fair Vote Canada]]|url=https://www.fairvote.ca/rural-urban-proportional/|title=Rural\u2013Urban Proportional|work=Fair Vote Canada|date=2018|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724151135/https://www.fairvote.ca/rural-urban-proportional/#|archive-date=24 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"fed-report\" /> As put forward for the BC referendum, it would use mixed-member proportional representation (MMP) in rural areas and the single transferable vote (STV) in urban and semi-urban areas.<ref name=\"systems\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/rural-urban-proportional-rup/ |title=Rural-Urban Proportional (RUP) |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |website=elections.bc.ca |access-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821093858/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/voting-systems/rural-urban-proportional-rup/# |archive-date=21 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4242810/british-columbians-will-vote-on-our-electoral-system-here-are-the-4-options/ |title=British Columbians will vote on our electoral system \u2014 Here are the 4 options |last=Zussman |first=Richard |work=[[Global News]] |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615004254/https://globalnews.ca/news/4242810/british-columbians-will-vote-on-our-electoral-system-here-are-the-4-options/# |archive-date=15 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Sweden, Denmark and Iceland use voting models with similar hybrid approaches. In Canada from the 1920s to the 1950s, the provinces of Alberta and Manitoba used a hybrid rural\u2013urban system where STV was used in large cities and the [[instant-runoff voting|alternative vote]] was used in single-member rural districts.<ref name=\"pdennis\"/>{{rp|81\u201382}}<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\"/><ref>{{Cite book| publisher = University of Michigan Press| isbn = 978-0-472-11159-6| editor1-last = Bowler| editor1-first = Shaun| editor2-last = Grofman| editor2-first = Bernard| title = Elections in Australia, Ireland, and Malta under the Single Transferable Vote| date = 2000| doi = 10.3998/mpub.16507| jstor = 10.3998/mpub.16507}}</ref>\n\nThe hybrid approach taken by rural\u2013urban proportional reflects lessons learned from previous attempts to pass electoral reform.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bcs-proportional-representation-voting-system-options-include-two |title=BC's proportional representation voting system options include two that are lesser known |last=Dhillon |first=Sunny |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=June 17, 2018 |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621183227/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bcs-proportional-representation-voting-system-options-include-two/# |archive-date=21 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> A major advantage of rural\u2013urban proportional as designed is that it requires creating far fewer top-up seats to achieve proportionality than MMP. Under rural\u2013urban PR, no more than 10\u201315% of seats \u2013 versus 40% of seats under MMP \u2013 would need to be set aside as top-up seats to achieve proportionality, because the results from the urban and semi-urban areas would already be proportional owing to their voting having been conducted using STV.\n\nFor rural areas, rural\u2013urban proportional is advantageous because existing first-past-the-post rural ridings need to grow only 15% larger to facilitate extra regional top-up seats under it, compared to 67% larger if MMP was chosen or double in size if DMP was chosen.<ref name=\"fairvote-ru\" />\n\nRUP is the only PR system of the three that lets voters rank individual candidates in order by preference. The use of STV ranked ballots means that all candidates must compete with one another for a voter's coveted first place ranking, including candidates running for the same party. Voters can rank long-shot independent candidates or candidates from unpopular parties first without fear of wasting their vote, because votes for badly performing candidates will be transferred during counting\u2014based on each voter's preferences\u2014to candidates who have yet to be eliminated, until all seats are won.\n\nIn its scorecard of proportional voting systems, Fair Voting BC gave rural\u2013urban proportional its highest ranking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fairvotingbc.com/scorecard/|title=Scorecard|author=Fair Voting BC|access-date=3 July 2018|publisher=Fair Voting BC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704092834/https://fairvotingbc.com/scorecard/#|archive-date=4 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[Government of Canada|Canadian government's]] 2016 consultation on electoral reform at the federal level,<ref name=\"fed-report\" /> both the [[New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party of Canada]] and [[Green Party of Canada]] recommended Canada adopt either RUP or MMP.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-electoral-reform-committee-1.3866879|title=Minister 'disappointed' as electoral reform committee recommends referendum on proportional representation|last1=Wherry|first1=Aaron|last2=Tasker|first2=John Paul|work=[[CBC News]]|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412133850/http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/wherry-electoral-reform-committee-1.3866879#|archive-date=12 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\nThe official campaign began July 1, 2018.<ref name=\"regulation\" /> Groups had until July 6 to apply to Elections BC to be named the official proponent or opponent groups and receive $500,000 in public funding.<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Funding |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/ |access-date=26 June 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034318/https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/# |archive-date=27 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  On July 12, Elections BC announced that Vote PR BC would be the official proponent group and No BC Proportional Representation Society would be the official opponent group.<ref>{{cite news |last=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Yes and No groups selected before B.C.'s electoral reform referendum |url=https://bc.ctvnews.ca/yes-and-no-groups-selected-before-b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4010867 |date=July 12, 2018 |access-date=14 July 2018 |work=[[CTV News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713191957/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/yes-and-no-groups-selected-before-b-c-s-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4010867# |archive-date=13 July 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Funding |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/ |access-date=14 July 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627034318/https://elections.bc.ca/referenda/2018-referendum-funding/# |archive-date=27 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Other individuals, groups and political parties are permitted to register as referendum advertisers with Elections BC, but are not eligible for public funds.<ref name=\"regulation\" />\n\nThe NDP and Green Party campaigned for proportional representation. [[Sonia Furstenau]], a Green [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia|MLA]], held town halls about electoral reform in cities across the province in July and August.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slack |first=Jeff |title=Green Party MLA holding forum on Electoral Reform in PG |url=https://www.myprincegeorgenow.com/80016/green-party-mla-holding-forum-on-electoral-reform-in-pg/ |date=July 19, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=My Prince George Now |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908015902/https://www.myprincegeorgenow.com/80016/green-party-mla-holding-forum-on-electoral-reform-in-pg/# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Staff |title=Green MLA Furstenau visits Nelson-Creston riding |url=http://thenelsondaily.com/news/green-mla-furstenau-visits-nelson-creston-riding#.W5LKksInaUk |date=August 21, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=Nelson Daily |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092736/http://thenelsondaily.com/news/green-mla-furstenau-visits-nelson-creston-riding#.W5LKksInaUk#.W5LKksInaUk |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Eckford |first=Sean |title=Simons and Green MLAs discuss PR, cooperation |url=https://www.coastreporter.net/news/local-news/simons-and-green-mlas-discuss-pr-cooperation-1.23412249 |date=August 24, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=Coast Reporter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092817/https://www.coastreporter.net/news/local-news/simons-and-green-mlas-discuss-pr-cooperation-1.23412249# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Premier of British Columbia|BC Premier]] [[John Horgan]] launched the NDP's referendum campaign in early September, saying \"Proportional representation means exactly what it says. Whatever proportion, or share, of the vote a party wins, they get that many seats in government.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Palmer |first=Vaughn |title=Horgan selling positives of electoral change, but there are negatives |url=https://vancouversun.com/opinion/columnists/vaughn-palmer-horgan-selling-positives-of-electoral-change-but-there-are-negatives |date=September 7, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907082937/https://vancouversun.com/opinion/columnists/vaughn-palmer-horgan-selling-positives-of-electoral-change-but-there-are-negatives# |archive-date=7 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Andrew Wilkinson]], BC Liberal leader, opposed the referendum and a change to a proportional representation system.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smyth |first=Mike |title=B.C. Liberals declare all-out war on proportional representation |url=https://theprovince.com/opinion/columnists/mike-smyth-liberals-declare-all-out-war-on-proportional-representation |date=June 3, 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908092836/https://theprovince.com/opinion/columnists/mike-smyth-liberals-declare-all-out-war-on-proportional-representation# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nElections BC mailed a referendum information card to every household in the province between September 10 and 28, and a voter's guide between October 15 and 26.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fletcher |first=Tom |title=Voter registration push begins for B.C. referendum |url=https://www.castlegarnews.com/news/voter-registration-push-begins-for-b-c-referendum/ |date=September 10, 2018 |access-date=10 September 2018 |work=Castlegar News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911045135/https://www.castlegarnews.com/news/voter-registration-push-begins-for-b-c-referendum/# |archive-date=11 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=EBCmail /> Voters received their referendum voting package in the mail between October 22 and November 2.<ref name=EBCmail>{{cite web |title=Referendum Resources |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/referendum-resources/ |access-date=11 September 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908015803/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/referendum-resources/# |archive-date=8 September 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In early September, the members of the [[Canadian Union of Postal Workers]] voted in favour of job action. The strike resulted in Elections BC extending the voting deadline by a week.<ref name=\"extension\" />\n\nIn early November, Horgan announced that he had cast his ballot for proportional representation, and that his first choice was MMP.<ref>{{cite news |last=CBC News |title=John Horgan: I voted for mixed-member proportional in electoral reform referendum |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/john-horgan-i-voted-for-mixed-member-proportional-in-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4888430 |date=November 1, 2018 |access-date=5 November 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104053556/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/john-horgan-i-voted-for-mixed-member-proportional-in-electoral-reform-referendum-1.4888430# |archive-date=4 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>  Vote PR BC, the official proponent group, flew Andrew Coyne to Vancouver to give a talk endorsing PR, where Coyne announced he supported Rural\u2013Urban Proportional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/voteprbc/photos/a.228311341063875/337164366845238/|title=Tomorrow noted political commentator @ACoyne joins us for a lively discussion on Pro Rep. Are you planning on taking part? RSVP here to attend: #PR4BC #ProRep #BCPoli|date=October 24, 2018|website=Facebook|access-date=8 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/andrew-coyne-which-electoral-system-for-b-c-any-option-is-better-than-the-status-quo |title=Andrew Coyne: Which electoral system for B.C.? Any option is better than the status quo |last=Coyne |first=Andrew |date=2018-10-30 |work=National Post |access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Debate ===\nIn late September, Andrew Wilkinson challenged John Horgan to a debate concerning the referendum, a challenge which Horgan accepted. The debate took place on November 8 at 7:00{{Nbsp}}pm. It was broadcast on [[CBC News]] and [[Global News]].<ref>{{cite news |last=CBC News |title=B.C. premier, opposition leader to face off in electoral reform debate |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/events/premier-opposition-leader-electoral-reform-debate-1.4883872 |date=October 30, 2018 |access-date=31 October 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030223159/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/events/premier-opposition-leader-electoral-reform-debate-1.4883872# |archive-date=30 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Official campaign organizations===\nOfficial campaign organizations include the official proponent and opponent groups along with referendum advertising sponsors.<ref name=RefSponsors>{{cite web |title=2018 Referendum Advertising Sponsors |url=https://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/2018-Referendum-Advertising-Sponsors.pdf |accessdate=8 December 2018 |publisher=Elections BC |website=elections.bc.ca |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208221641/https://elections.bc.ca/docs/referendum/2018-Referendum-Advertising-Sponsors.pdf |archive-date=8 December 2018 |url-status=live  |date=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Official proponent and opponent groups====\n\n* Proponent: Vote PR BC\n* Opponent: No BC Proportional Representation Society\n\n====Referendum advertising sponsors====\n* Asian Environmental Association\n* [[British Columbia Conservative Party]]\n* [[British Columbia Government and Service Employees' Union]]\n* British Columbia Liberal Party\n* British Columbia New Democratic Party\n* Committee for Voting Equity in BC\n* [[Communist Party of British Columbia]]\n* [[Dogwood Initiative]]\n* Fair Vote Canada BC\n* Fraser Valley East Against Proportional Representation\n* Green Party Political Association of British Columbia\n* KnowB4UVote.com Society\n* [[LeadNow]]\n* No Pro Rep Fraser Valley East \n* Rural\u2013Urban Proportional for BC\n* Wake Up BC\n* Wildsight\n* Wise Vote BC\n* YES or NO, Rural Urban First\n\n==Voting period extension==\nOn November 23, 2018, due to a postal strike, Elections BC extended the voting period deadline by a week \u2013 from November 30, 2018, to December 7, 2018.<ref name=\"extension\">{{cite news |title=Voting period for electoral reform referendum extended due to postal strike |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/electoral-referendum-deadline-extended-1.4918055 |access-date=23 November 2018 |work=CBC News |date=November 23, 2018}}</ref> The deadline to register to vote remained midnight on November 23, 2018. Voters who were sent a voting package but did not receive it, or who need a replacement voting package, could request a replacement package up to December 7. All ballots must have been received by Elections BC by 4:30{{Nbsp}}pm on December 7.<ref>https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/how-to-vote</ref> In response to a question from a constituent on [[Twitter]], Elections BC clarified that ballots received by Elections BC's Referendum Service Offices or Service BC Centres up to and including 4:30{{Nbsp}}pm on December 7, 2018, but which had not been physically transferred to Elections BC's counting centre, would be accepted and counted as valid ballots.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ElectionsBC |number=1073637787738357761 |date=December 14, 2018 |access-date=December 19, 2018 |author=Elections BC |author-link=Elections BC |title=Hi Doug \u2013 Yes, completed voting packages received by Elections BC by mail or in person at a Referendum Service Office or Service BC Centre by 4:30 p.m. on December 7, 2018 were accepted for counting.}}</ref>\n\n==Post-referendum plans==\n\nThe government had plans for the required next steps had proportional representation passed. However, as it did not pass, the government will not implement any of these steps.  Had a proportional system been adopted, the independent [[British Columbia Electoral Boundaries Commission|BC Electoral Boundaries Commission]] would have determined the number and location of new electoral districts. A legislative committee would have been tasked with determining whether the number of members of the Legislative Assembly should increase, and if so by how many (to a maximum of an additional eight). Some other aspects of how the new system would have worked would have also needed to be determined by a legislative committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/what-are-we-voting-on/ |title=What happens after the referendum? |website=elections.bc.ca |publisher=[[Elections BC]] |access-date=24 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073911/https://elections.bc.ca/referendum/what-are-we-voting-on/# |archive-date=25 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIf a form of proportional representation had been adopted, the government had also committed to holding a further confirming referendum after two general elections.<ref name=\"2018report\" /><ref name=\"PremierStatement\" /> Voters in that future referendum would have had the option of maintaining the form of proportional representation adopted or switching back to the first-past-the-post electoral system.<ref name=\"Tyee?s\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4259321/bc-electoral-reform-referendum-format/|title=B.C. cabinet confirms format of electoral reform referendum|last=Zussman|first=Richard|work=[[Global News]]|date=June 7, 2018|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612165225/https://globalnews.ca/news/4259321/bc-electoral-reform-referendum-format/#|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 2, 2018, the government introduced legislation to enact the requirement for this second referendum into law. If a change from the first-past-the-post system had been adopted in 2018, the bill would have required a second referendum on electoral reform to occur within 13 months of the second provincial general election held under the chosen proportional representation voting system (no later than November 30, 2026). As voters decided to keep the existing first-past-the-post system, this second referendum will not take place.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4509590/b-c-government-second-referendum-electoral-reform/ |title=B.C. Government to legislate a second referendum on electoral reform if new system passes |last=Zussman |first=Richard |work=[[Global News]] |date=October 2, 2018 |access-date=3 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002223022/https://globalnews.ca/news/4509590/b-c-government-second-referendum-electoral-reform/# |archive-date=2 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cheknews.ca/legislation-proposed-for-a-confirming-referendum-if-b-c-voters-choose-proportional-representation-494941/|title=Legislation proposed for a confirming referendum if B.C. voters choose proportional representation|last=CHEK News|work=[[CHEK-DT|CHEK News]]|date=October 2, 2018|access-date=3 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004103735/https://www.cheknews.ca/legislation-proposed-for-a-confirming-referendum-if-b-c-voters-choose-proportional-representation-494941/#|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polls==\n\n===Question 1===\n\nReferendum-style binary question<br />Question: \"Based on what you know, please indicate which of these two broad options you prefer for BC\"\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Polling firm\n!Last date of polling\n!A new system of proportional representation\n!The current first-past-the-post system\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|June 20, 2017\n|59%\n|41%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/bc-post-election/|title=Snap Election? Snap out of it, say majority of British Columbians - Angus Reid Institute|date=2017-06-17|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080258/http://angusreid.org/bc-post-election/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|Sept 26, 2017\n|65%\n|35%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/horgan-ndp-electoral-reform-energy-projects/|title=British Columbians call on new provincial government to deliver electoral reform, energy projects - Angus Reid Institute|date=2017-09-25|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080256/http://angusreid.org/horgan-ndp-electoral-reform-energy-projects/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|December 31, 2017\n|57%\n|43%\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://angusreid.org/site-c-horgan/|title=Site C: By margin of two-to-one, BC residents say province made the right call to finish dam project - Angus Reid Institute|date=2018-01-11|work=Angus Reid Institute|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023080253/http://angusreid.org/site-c-horgan/#|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|Angus Reid\n|May 9, 2018\n|57%\n|43%\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://angusreid.org/bc-ndp-one-year/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929194838/http://angusreid.org/bc-ndp-one-year/# |archive-d